{"title_page": "Walter Riccomi", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name        = Walter Riccomi\n| image       = Walter Riccomi c1973.jpg\n| caption     = Riccomi in 1973\n| full_name   = Walter Riccomi\n| nickname    = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1950|1|18|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Montecarlo, Tuscany|Montecarlo]], [[Italy]]\n| height      = \n| weight      = \n| currentteam = Retired\n| discipline  = Road\n| role        = Rider\n| ridertype   = \n| proyears1   = \n| proteam1    = \n| majorwins   = \n}}\n'''Walter Riccomi''' (born 18 January 1950) is a retired Italian professional [[road bicycle racer]]. Riccomi finished in the top ten of a [[Grand Tour (cycling)|grand tour]] four times, but did not win any stage.<ref>{{Cycling Archives|4431}}</ref> He also competed in the [[Cycling at the 1972 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's individual road race|individual road race]] at the [[1972 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ri/walter-riccomi-1.html |title=Walter Riccomi Olympic Results |accessdate=19 October 2014 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n== Palmar\u00e8s ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n;1975\n:[[1975 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]:\n::7th place overall classification\n;1976\n:Castiglione del Lago\n:[[Gran Premio Citt\u00e0 di Camaiore]]\n:[[Gran Premio Industria e Commercio di Prato]]\n:[[1976 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]:\n::9th place overall classification\n:[[1976 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::5th place overall classification\n;1977\n:GP Aix-en-Provence\n:[[1977 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]:\n::7th place overall classification\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Walter Riccomi}}\n*{{Tour de France results|4323|archive=20070808162814}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Riccomi, Walter}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1972 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Italy]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Lucca]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Tuscany]]\n\n\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1950s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name        = Walter Riccomi\n| image       = Walter Riccomi c1973.jpg\n| caption     = Riccomi in 1973\n| full_name   = Walter Riccomi\n| nickname    = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1950|1|18|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Montecarlo, Tuscany|Montecarlo]], [[Italy]]\n| height      = \n| weight      = \n| currentteam = Retired\n| discipline  = Road\n| role        = Rider\n| ridertype   = \n| proyears1   = \n| proteam1    = \n| majorwins   = \n}}\n'''Walter Riccomi''' (born 18 January 1950) is a retired Italian professional [[road bicycle racer]]. Riccomi finished in the top ten of a [[Grand Tour (cycling)|grand tour]] four times, but did not win any stage.<ref>{{Cycling Archives|4431}}</ref> He also competed in the [[Cycling at the 1972 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's individual road race|individual road race]] at the [[1972 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ri/walter-riccomi-1.html |title=Walter Riccomi Olympic Results |accessdate=19 October 2014 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n== Palmar\u00e8s ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n;1975\n:[[1975 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]:\n::7th place overall classification\n;1976\n:Castiglione del Lago\n:[[Gran Premio Citt\u00e0 di Camaiore]]\n:[[Gran Premio Industria e Commercio di Prato]]\n:[[1976 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]:\n::9th place overall classification\n:[[1976 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::5th place overall classification\n;1977\n:GP Aix-en-Provence\n:[[1977 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]:\n::7th place overall classification\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Walter Riccomi}}\n*{{Tour de France results|4323|archive=20070808162814}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Riccomi, Walter}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1972 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Italy]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Lucca]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Tuscany]]\n\n\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1950s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Riccomi"}
{"title_page": "Allan Carr", "text_new": "{{about|the American stage and film producer|the British comedian|Alan Carr|other people with a similar name|Alan Carr (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                  = Allan Carr\n| image                 = Allan Carr at 1989 Academy Awards.jpg\n| caption               = Allan Carr at the 1989 Academy Awards\n| birth_name            = Allan Solomon\n| birth_date            = {{Birth date|1937|05|27}}\n| birth_place           = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date            = {{Death date and age|1999|06|29|1937|05|27}}\n| death_place           = [[Beverly Hills, California]], U.S.\n| nationality           = American\n| education             = [[Lake Forest College]]\n| alma_mater            = [[Northwestern University]]\n| occupation            = Producer, screenwriter\n| years_active          = 1969\u20131998\n}}\n\n'''Allan Carr''' (born '''Allan Soloman''', May 27, 1937 \u2013 June 29, 1999) was an American producer and manager of stage for the [[film|screen]]. Carr was nominated for numerous awards, winning a [[Tony Award]] and two [[People's Choice Awards]], and was named Producer of the Year by the National Association of Theatre Owners.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news| url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_1999_June_30/ai_55029330|work=Business Wire|title=Allan Carr, Producer, Impresario, Manager and Showman, Dies at 62|date=June 30, 1999}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nCarr was born '''Allan Solomon'''<ref>[http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20074272,00.html People Magazine: \"Producer Allan Carr Waxes Fat and Fortyish on the Gross of Grease\" By Sue Reilly] August 06, 1979</ref> to an [[American Jewish]] family<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iqRezpQzUcAC&q=jewish#v=onepage&q=jewish%2C%20or%20not&f=false|first=Robert|last=Hofler|title=Party Animals: A Hollywood Tale of Sex, Drugs, and Rock N Roll Starring the Fabulous Allan Carr|pages=95|publisher=|date=Dec 28, 2012|isbn=9781459600072}}</ref> in Chicago, Illinois. He attended [[Lake Forest College]] and [[Northwestern University]], but his interest was always in show business. While at Northwestern, he invested $750 in the Broadway musical ''Ziegfeld Follies,'' starring [[Tallulah Bankhead]]. Though the show was not a hit, he had also invested $1,250 in 1967's ''[[The Happiest Millionaire]],'' which gave him the success he needed to leave school and embark upon a career in entertainment.\n\nIn Chicago in the 1960s, he opened the Civic Theater and financed ''[[The World of Carl Sandburg]]'' starring [[Bette Davis]] and [[Gary Merrill]], as well as [[Eva Le Gallienne]] in ''[[Mary Stuart (play)|Mary Stuart]],'' directed by Sir [[Tyrone Guthrie]], and [[Tennessee Williams]]'s ''Garden District'', featuring [[Cathleen Nesbitt]] and [[Diana Barrymore]]. Carr worked behind the scenes at ''[[Playboy]]'' with [[Hugh Hefner]] and was a co-creator of the ''Playboy Penthouse'' television series, which in turn launched the [[Playboy Club]]s.\n\nThrough the years, he became known as a great planner of promotional events and parties. One such event, a black-tie affair for [[Truman Capote]], took place in an abandoned Los Angeles jail.<ref name=Y>{{cite web|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/allan-carr-rise-fall-hollywood-hedonist-014130665.html|title=Allan Carr: The rise and fall of a Hollywood hedonist|author=Taggart, Frankie|date=May 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Management career==\nIn 1966, Carr founded the talent agency Allan Carr Enterprises, managing the actors [[Tony Curtis]], [[Peter Sellers]],<ref name=Y/> [[Rosalind Russell]], [[Dyan Cannon]], [[Melina Mercouri]], and [[Marlo Thomas]].  Some of the other entertainment figures whose careers he managed were [[Ann-Margret]], a string of whose television specials he also produced, [[Nancy Walker]], [[Marvin Hamlisch]], [[Joan Rivers]], [[Peggy Lee]], \"Mama\" [[Cass Elliot]],<ref name=Y/> [[Paul Anka]], [[Frankie Valli and the Four Seasons]], [[George Maharis]], and [[Herb Alpert and the Tijuana Brass]].\n\nCarr is also credited for having discovered numerous celebrities, including some such, who also became his clients, as [[Olivia Newton-John]], [[Mark Hamill]], [[Michelle Pfeiffer]],<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/96824/Allan-Carr Allan Carr \u2013 Britannica Online Encyclopedia<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[Steve Guttenberg]],<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/07/01/arts/allan-carr-62-the-producer-of-grease-and-la-cage.html|work=The New York Times|title=Allan Carr, 62, the Producer Of 'Grease' and 'La Cage'|date=July 1, 1999|accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref> and [[Lisa Hartman]].<ref name=autogenerated1/>\n\n==''Grease'' and Broadway success==\nProducer [[Robert Stigwood]] hired him in 1975 as marketing and promotion consultant, with his first project being for the [[Tommy (1975 film)|film version]] of the [[rock opera]] ''[[The Who's Tommy|Tommy]]''.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> The film was a hit and he expanded his involvement for his next film, re-editing and overdubbing a low-budget foreign film about a real-life disaster. The result was ''Survive!'' (The disaster in question was also described in Piers Paul Read's book ''Alive.'') The surprise box office success of ''Survive!'' in 1976 made Carr a wealthy man and gave him clout at [[Paramount Pictures]].\n\nIn 1977, Stigwood asked him to produce the ad campaign for ''[[Saturday Night Fever]],'' and he turned the film's premiere into a star-studded television special. It worked so well that Stigwood gave him ''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]'' (1978). Carr not only helmed the ad campaign and produced the premiere party and television special for ''Grease,'' but also wrote the screenplay and co-produced the film for six million dollars, casting his then client [[Olivia Newton-John]].<ref name=Y/> It became the highest-grossing film of the year, and one of the highest-grossing films up until that time, at just under $100 million. The film was nominated for five [[Golden Globe Awards]] and won two [[People's Choice Awards]], for Best Picture and Best Musical Picture. That year he even appeared in a role on the final season of the [[Angie Dickinson]] television series ''[[Police Woman (TV series)|Police Woman]]''. Stigwood and Carr would work on several other films, including 1978 [[Academy Award|Oscar]]-winner ''[[The Deer Hunter]]''.\n\nThe following year, 1979, he produced the [[Village People]] film musical ''[[Can't Stop the Music|Can't Stop The Music]],''<ref name=Y/> a production which, while campy, steered clear of addressing the band members' presumed homosexuality in the script. Again he orchestrated a lavish series of premieres and a television special that co-starred his friends Hefner and [[Cher]]. But the film was released in 1980, after the crash of the disco craze, and as a result, it was a major flop.<ref name=Y/> Because of this, Carr \"won\" the first annual [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Picture]] in 1981. Undaunted, he went on to produce ''[[Grease 2]]'' (1982) which, while nowhere near the hit of its predecessor, was not the financial loss that ''Can't Stop The Music'' had been.\n\nWhen Carr was in Paris for the premiere of ''Grease,'' a friend took him to see a play about a gay couple, ''[[La Cage aux Folles (play)|La Cage aux Folles]].'' By this time in his career, Carr was ready to face the gay theme head on. Returning to Broadway he produced [[La Cage aux Folles (musical)|a musical version]] of the 1973 play,<ref name=Y/> which had since been made into a French film, and would later be remade as an American film called ''[[The Birdcage]].'' With a book by [[Harvey Fierstein]] and music and lyrics by [[Jerry Herman]], the show opened in 1983 and was a huge success, running for five years and 1,761 performances.  Nominated in 1984 for eight [[Drama Desk Award]]s and eight [[Tony Award]]s, the show won three Drama Desks and an impressive six Tonys, including a \"Best Musical\" win for Carr.\n\n==Snow White and the Academy Awards==\nCarr's reputation for hosting expensive and lavish parties and creating spectacular production numbers led [[AMPAS]]  to hire him to produce the [[61st Academy Awards]] and create the show based on his promise that he would turn it around from the dry, dull show it had been in previous years. It was inspired by ''[[Beach Blanket Babylon]]'', the musical revue show featuring [[Snow White]] at Hollywood after the dwarves during the [[Golden Age of Hollywood]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_AyU_EbgFlc Bruce Vilanch on \"The 1989 Oscars\" with Rob Lowe and Snow White - FoundationINTERVIEWS on YouTube]</ref> Promising \"the antithesis of tacky,\" and despite the best Nielson ratings in five years, it proved to be a career disaster for Allan, culminating in the infamous pairing of Snow White (played by Eileen Bowman) and [[Rob Lowe]] singing a parody of \"[[Proud Mary]].\"<ref name=Y/> Before that, when Snow White first entered the theater from the rear, she seemed to surprise and even put-off the movie stars she was singing to, using a high-pitched imitation (bordering on parody) of the Disney cartoon. During the main number, before Rob Lowe's entrance, a crooning Merv Griffin introduced a procession of once famous Hollywood stars ranging from Alice Faye to Roy Rogers and Dale Evans to Vincent Price, which seemed more forced than natural as the elders were practically guided across the stage by male dancers (some dressed as chairs and tables). Also, there was no host that year. Instead, actors and actresses traded off, ranging from Tom Selleck (who opened) to Bob Hope and Lucille Ball (the latter died three weeks later). His no host theme was centered on \"compadres, costars, couples and companions,\" and his no host theme wouldn't be repeated until the Oscars of 2019.\n\nThe telecast also included a production number featuring what was introduced as \"The Stars of Tomorrow\" doing a number entitled \"I Wanna Be An Oscar Winner\" with all the participants being actors and actresses ranging from the age group of late teens to mid-20s (including Corey Feldman doing a Michael Jackson impression; Christian Slater sword fighting with Tyrone Power Jr.; Chad Lowe shouting \"I am a Thespian\"; Tracy Nelson ballet dancing; Patrick Dempsey tap dancing along the central set stairwell).<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uAQ9Taunh7w The Stars of Tomorrow: 1989 Oscars]</ref> Due largely to the show's opening number, and despite the shows stellar Nielson ratings, the show became a laughing-stock and went down in history as one of the worst moments in awards show and television history.  [[The Walt Disney Company]] sued for allegedly illegal use of Snow White's image.<ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/looking-back-oscars-biggest-goof-21211 Looking back at Oscar's biggest goof|Hollywood Reporter]</ref> Meanwhile, Gregory Peck (a personal friend of Carr's) and a number of actors wrote and signed a letter of protest, demanding there never be a show like that again; Peck, in fact, threatened to return his past Oscar if it was ever repeated, which it wasn't. \n\nCarr's reputation in Hollywood never fully recovered from this setback, although his decision to change the award announcement from \"And the winner is...\" to \"And the Oscar goes to...\"<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PT7g5pWzOyw Why the 1989 Oscars Are the Worst Ever - Metaflix on YouTube]</ref> became the norm for awards shows in general, not just for the Oscars. Carr also first hired comedian [[Bruce Vilanch]] as head comedy writer of the show, a job Vilanch still held as of 2015 (Vilanch was redeemed the following year since his old friend Billy Crystal hosted for his first of many times: with Vilanch as his head writer).\n\n==Later work==\nThat same year Carr helmed the project ''Goya...A Life in Song'' with Freddie Gershon and CBS Records, a concept album and, later, an off-Broadway musical theater production written by [[Maury Yeston]] (''[[Nine (musical)|Nine]]'') and featuring [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]] as artist [[Francisco Goya]].  Still in development for a full Broadway production, the music has been recorded by Domingo with [[Dionne Warwick]] in English and [[Gloria Estefan]] in Spanish, and a version of the duet \"[[Till I Loved You (song)|Till I Loved You]]\" was a top 40 single for [[Barbra Streisand]] and [[Don Johnson]].\n\nCarr continued his work in theater, sponsoring the 1995 [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] productions of ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]'' and ''[[Much Ado About Nothing]]'' at [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]]'s [[Kennedy Center]] and Broadway's [[Gershwin Theatre]]<ref>[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1999-jun-30-mn-51594-story.html Allan Carr; Producer of 'Grease' and 'La Cage aux Folles' - Los Angeles Times]</ref>, earning 10 Tony nominations between them including one more for Carr.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-allan-carr-1105920.html Obituary: Allan Carr|The Independent]</ref>\nCarr had returned to [[Paramount Pictures]] to handle the re-release of ''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]'' in 1998, which included producing a [[VH1]] television special of the twentieth anniversary Hollywood \"premiere\" screening and party, and special edition re-releases of the video, DVD, and soundtrack album.\n\n==Production career==\nCarr was a film producer for numerous movies, including:\n*''[[The First Time (1969 film)|The First Time]]'' (1969)\n*''[[C.C. and Company]]'' (1970)\n*''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]'' (1978)\n*''[[Can't Stop the Music]]'' (1980)\n*''[[Grease 2]]'' (1982)\n*''[[Where the Boys Are '84]]'' (1984)\n*''[[Cloak & Dagger (1984 film)|Cloak & Dagger]]'' (1984)\n\n==Personal life and death==\nCarr died on June 29, 1999, in [[Beverly Hills, California]] from [[liver cancer]].<ref name=Y/> At the time of his death, he split his time between his homes in Beverly Hills and [[Palm Springs, California|Palm Springs]], and was working on bringing [[Ken Ludwig]]'s Tony-winning comedy ''[[Lend Me a Tenor]]'' to Australia and the UK, and was preparing a new Broadway show, ''The New Musical Adventures of Tom Sawyer''.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\nHis ashes were scattered at sea by Ann-Margret, Roger Smith and Martin Menard in front of his former Diamond Head estate on the island of Oahu, Hawaii.\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2017 a documentary about Carr's life was released entitled ''[[The Fabulous Allan Carr]]''.  The director of ''The Fabulous Allan Carr'' [[Jeffrey Schwarz]] said, \"Although it was no secret that Allan Carr was gay, he never formally acknowledged it publicly. The word 'flamboyant' was used to describe him, a code word.\"<ref name=Y/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0139591}}\n* {{Find a Grave|23458|accessdate=September 14, 2010}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9mronRVvdmw The infamous 1989 opening of the Oscars on YouTube]\n* [https://vimeo.com/221448144 The same opening also on Vimeo]\n\n{{Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screenplay 1980\u20132000}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carr, Allan}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:Film producers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Television producers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Jewish American screenwriters]]\n[[Category:LGBT Jews]]\n[[Category:Gay entertainers]]\n[[Category:LGBT businesspeople from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from California]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Illinois]]\n[[Category:American theatre managers and producers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in California]]\n[[Category:Deaths from liver cancer]]\n[[Category:Lake Forest College alumni]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Television producers from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Illinois]]\n[[Category:LGBT producers]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the American stage and film producer|the British comedian|Alan Carr|other people with a similar name|Alan Carr (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                  = Allan Carr\n| image                 = Allan Carr at 1989 Academy Awards.jpg\n| caption               = Allan Carr at the 1989 Academy Awards\n| birth_name            = Allan Solomon\n| birth_date            = {{Birth date|1937|05|27}}\n| birth_place           = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date            = {{Death date and age|1999|06|29|1937|05|27}}\n| death_place           = [[Beverly Hills, California]], U.S.\n| nationality           = American\n| education             = [[Lake Forest College]]\n| alma_mater            = [[Northwestern University]]\n| occupation            = Producer, screenwriter\n| years_active          = 1969\u20131998\n}}\n\n'''Allan Carr''' (born '''Allan Soloman''', May 27, 1937 \u2013 June 29, 1999) was an American producer and manager of stage for the [[film|screen]]. Carr was nominated for numerous awards, winning a [[Tony Award]] and two [[People's Choice Awards]], and was named Producer of the Year by the National Association of Theatre Owners.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news| url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_1999_June_30/ai_55029330|work=Business Wire|title=Allan Carr, Producer, Impresario, Manager and Showman, Dies at 62|date=June 30, 1999}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nCarr was born '''Allan Solomon'''<ref>[http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20074272,00.html People Magazine: \"Producer Allan Carr Waxes Fat and Fortyish on the Gross of Grease\" By Sue Reilly] August 06, 1979</ref> to an [[American Jewish]] family<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iqRezpQzUcAC&q=jewish#v=onepage&q=jewish%2C%20or%20not&f=false|first=Robert|last=Hofler|title=Party Animals: A Hollywood Tale of Sex, Drugs, and Rock N Roll Starring the Fabulous Allan Carr|pages=95|publisher=|date=Dec 28, 2012|isbn=9781459600072}}</ref> in Chicago, Illinois. He attended [[Lake Forest College]] and [[Northwestern University]], but his interest was always in show business. While at Northwestern, he invested $750 in the Broadway musical ''Ziegfeld Follies,'' starring [[Tallulah Bankhead]]. Though the show was not a hit, he had also invested $1,250 in 1967's ''[[The Happiest Millionaire]],'' which gave him the success he needed to leave school and embark upon a career in entertainment.\n\nIn Chicago in the 1960s, he opened the Civic Theater and financed ''[[The World of Carl Sandburg]]'' starring [[Bette Davis]] and [[Gary Merrill]], as well as [[Eva Le Gallienne]] in ''[[Mary Stuart (play)|Mary Stuart]],'' directed by Sir [[Tyrone Guthrie]], and [[Tennessee Williams]]'s ''Garden District'', featuring [[Cathleen Nesbitt]] and [[Diana Barrymore]]. Carr worked behind the scenes at ''[[Playboy]]'' with [[Hugh Hefner]] and was a co-creator of the ''Playboy Penthouse'' television series, which in turn launched the [[Playboy Club]]s.\n\nThrough the years, he became known as a great planner of promotional events and parties. One such event, a black-tie affair for [[Truman Capote]], took place in an abandoned Los Angeles jail.<ref name=Y>{{cite web|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/allan-carr-rise-fall-hollywood-hedonist-014130665.html|title=Allan Carr: The rise and fall of a Hollywood hedonist|author=Taggart, Frankie|date=May 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Management career==\nIn 1966, Carr founded the talent agency Allan Carr Enterprises, managing the actors [[Tony Curtis]], [[Peter Sellers]],<ref name=Y/> [[Rosalind Russell]], [[Dyan Cannon]], [[Melina Mercouri]], and [[Marlo Thomas]].  Some of the other entertainment figures whose careers he managed were [[Ann-Margret]], a string of whose television specials he also produced, [[Nancy Walker]], [[Marvin Hamlisch]], [[Joan Rivers]], [[Peggy Lee]], \"Mama\" [[Cass Elliot]],<ref name=Y/> [[Paul Anka]], [[Frankie Valli and the Four Seasons]], [[George Maharis]], and [[Herb Alpert and the Tijuana Brass]].\n\nCarr is also credited for having discovered numerous celebrities, including some such, who also became his clients, as [[Olivia Newton-John]], [[Mark Hamill]], [[Michelle Pfeiffer]],<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/96824/Allan-Carr Allan Carr \u2013 Britannica Online Encyclopedia<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[Steve Guttenberg]],<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/07/01/arts/allan-carr-62-the-producer-of-grease-and-la-cage.html|work=The New York Times|title=Allan Carr, 62, the Producer Of 'Grease' and 'La Cage'|date=July 1, 1999|accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref> and [[Lisa Hartman]].<ref name=autogenerated1/>\n\n==''Grease'' and Broadway success==\nProducer [[Robert Stigwood]] hired him in 1975 as marketing and promotion consultant, with his first project being for the [[Tommy (1975 film)|film version]] of the [[rock opera]] ''[[The Who's Tommy|Tommy]]''.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> The film was a hit and he expanded his involvement for his next film, re-editing and overdubbing a low-budget foreign film about a real-life disaster. The result was ''Survive!'' (The disaster in question was also described in Piers Paul Read's book ''Alive.'') The surprise box office success of ''Survive!'' in 1976 made Carr a wealthy man and gave him clout at [[Paramount Pictures]].\n\nIn 1977, Stigwood asked him to produce the ad campaign for ''[[Saturday Night Fever]],'' and he turned the film's premiere into a star-studded television special. It worked so well that Stigwood gave him ''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]'' (1978). Carr not only helmed the ad campaign and produced the premiere party and television special for ''Grease,'' but also wrote the screenplay and co-produced the film for six million dollars, casting his then client [[Olivia Newton-John]].<ref name=Y/> It became the highest-grossing film of the year, and one of the highest-grossing films up until that time, at just under $100 million. The film was nominated for five [[Golden Globe Awards]] and won two [[People's Choice Awards]], for Best Picture and Best Musical Picture. That year he even appeared in a role on the final season of the [[Angie Dickinson]] television series ''[[Police Woman (TV series)|Police Woman]]''. Stigwood and Carr would work on several other films, including 1978 [[Academy Award|Oscar]]-winner ''[[The Deer Hunter]]''.\n\nThe following year, 1979, he produced the [[Village People]] film musical ''[[Can't Stop the Music|Can't Stop The Music]],''<ref name=Y/> a production which, while campy, steered clear of addressing the band members' presumed homosexuality in the script. Again he orchestrated a lavish series of premieres and a television special that co-starred his friends Hefner and [[Cher]]. But the film was released in 1980, after the crash of the disco craze, and as a result, it was a major flop.<ref name=Y/> Because of this, Carr \"won\" the first annual [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Picture]] in 1981. Undaunted, he went on to produce ''[[Grease 2]]'' (1982) which, while nowhere near the hit of its predecessor, was not the financial loss that ''Can't Stop The Music'' had been.\n\nWhen Carr was in Paris for the premiere of ''Grease,'' a friend took him to see a play about a gay couple, ''[[La Cage aux Folles (play)|La Cage aux Folles]].'' By this time in his career, Carr was ready to face the gay theme head on. Returning to Broadway he produced a musical version of the 1973 play,<ref name=Y/> which had since been made into a French film, and would later be remade as an American film called ''[[The Birdcage]].'' With a book by [[Harvey Fierstein]] and music and lyrics by [[Jerry Herman]], the show opened in 1983 and was a huge success, running for five years and 1,761 performances.  Nominated in 1984 for eight [[Drama Desk Award]]s and eight [[Tony Award]]s, the show won three Drama Desks and an impressive six Tonys, including a \"Best Musical\" win for Carr.\n\n==Snow White and the Academy Awards==\nCarr's reputation for hosting expensive and lavish parties and creating spectacular production numbers led [[AMPAS]]  to hire him to produce the [[61st Academy Awards]] and create the show based on his promise that he would turn it around from the dry, dull show it had been in previous years. It was inspired by ''[[Beach Blanket Babylon]]'', the musical revue show featuring [[Snow White]] at Hollywood after the dwarves during the [[Golden Age of Hollywood]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_AyU_EbgFlc Bruce Vilanch on \"The 1989 Oscars\" with Rob Lowe and Snow White - FoundationINTERVIEWS on YouTube]</ref> Promising \"the antithesis of tacky,\" and despite the best Nielson ratings in five years, it proved to be a career disaster for Allan, culminating in the infamous pairing of Snow White (played by Eileen Bowman) and [[Rob Lowe]] singing a parody of \"[[Proud Mary]].\"<ref name=Y/> Before that, when Snow White first entered the theater from the rear, she seemed to surprise and even put-off the movie stars she was singing to, using a high-pitched imitation (bordering on parody) of the Disney cartoon. During the main number, before Rob Lowe's entrance, a crooning Merv Griffin introduced a procession of once famous Hollywood stars ranging from Alice Faye to Roy Rogers and Dale Evans to Vincent Price, which seemed more forced than natural as the elders were practically guided across the stage by male dancers (some dressed as chairs and tables). Also, there was no host that year. Instead, actors and actresses traded off, ranging from Tom Selleck (who opened) to Bob Hope and Lucille Ball (the latter died three weeks later). His no host theme was centered on \"compadres, costars, couples and companions,\" and his no host theme wouldn't be repeated until the Oscars of 2019.\n\nThe telecast also included a production number featuring what was introduced as \"The Stars of Tomorrow\" doing a number entitled \"I Wanna Be An Oscar Winner\" with all the participants being actors and actresses ranging from the age group of late teens to mid-20s (including Corey Feldman doing a Michael Jackson impression; Christian Slater sword fighting with Tyrone Power Jr.; Chad Lowe shouting \"I am a Thespian\"; Tracy Nelson ballet dancing; Patrick Dempsey tap dancing along the central set stairwell).<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uAQ9Taunh7w The Stars of Tomorrow: 1989 Oscars]</ref> Due largely to the show's opening number, and despite the shows stellar Nielson ratings, the show became a laughing-stock and went down in history as one of the worst moments in awards show and television history.  [[The Walt Disney Company]] sued for allegedly illegal use of Snow White's image.<ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/looking-back-oscars-biggest-goof-21211 Looking back at Oscar's biggest goof|Hollywood Reporter]</ref> Meanwhile, Gregory Peck (a personal friend of Carr's) and a number of actors wrote and signed a letter of protest, demanding there never be a show like that again; Peck, in fact, threatened to return his past Oscar if it was ever repeated, which it wasn't. \n\nCarr's reputation in Hollywood never fully recovered from this setback, although his decision to change the award announcement from \"And the winner is...\" to \"And the Oscar goes to...\"<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PT7g5pWzOyw Why the 1989 Oscars Are the Worst Ever - Metaflix on YouTube]</ref> became the norm for awards shows in general, not just for the Oscars. Carr also first hired comedian [[Bruce Vilanch]] as head comedy writer of the show, a job Vilanch still held as of 2015 (Vilanch was redeemed the following year since his old friend Billy Crystal hosted for his first of many times: with Vilanch as his head writer).\n\n==Later work==\nThat same year Carr helmed the project ''Goya...A Life in Song'' with Freddie Gershon and CBS Records, a concept album and, later, an off-Broadway musical theater production written by [[Maury Yeston]] (''[[Nine (musical)|Nine]]'') and featuring [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]] as artist [[Francisco Goya]].  Still in development for a full Broadway production, the music has been recorded by Domingo with [[Dionne Warwick]] in English and [[Gloria Estefan]] in Spanish, and a version of the duet \"[[Till I Loved You (song)|Till I Loved You]]\" was a top 40 single for [[Barbra Streisand]] and [[Don Johnson]].\n\nCarr continued his work in theater, sponsoring the 1995 [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] productions of ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]'' and ''[[Much Ado About Nothing]]'' at [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]]'s [[Kennedy Center]] and Broadway's [[Gershwin Theatre]]<ref>[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1999-jun-30-mn-51594-story.html Allan Carr; Producer of 'Grease' and 'La Cage aux Folles' - Los Angeles Times]</ref>, earning 10 Tony nominations between them including one more for Carr.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-allan-carr-1105920.html Obituary: Allan Carr|The Independent]</ref>\nCarr had returned to [[Paramount Pictures]] to handle the re-release of ''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]'' in 1998, which included producing a [[VH1]] television special of the twentieth anniversary Hollywood \"premiere\" screening and party, and special edition re-releases of the video, DVD, and soundtrack album.\n\n==Production career==\nCarr was a film producer for numerous movies, including:\n*''[[The First Time (1969 film)|The First Time]]'' (1969)\n*''[[C.C. and Company]]'' (1970)\n*''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]'' (1978)\n*''[[Can't Stop the Music]]'' (1980)\n*''[[Grease 2]]'' (1982)\n*''[[Where the Boys Are '84]]'' (1984)\n*''[[Cloak & Dagger (1984 film)|Cloak & Dagger]]'' (1984)\n\n==Personal life and death==\nCarr died on June 29, 1999, in [[Beverly Hills, California]] from [[liver cancer]].<ref name=Y/> At the time of his death, he split his time between his homes in Beverly Hills and [[Palm Springs, California|Palm Springs]], and was working on bringing [[Ken Ludwig]]'s Tony-winning comedy ''[[Lend Me a Tenor]]'' to Australia and the UK, and was preparing a new Broadway show, ''The New Musical Adventures of Tom Sawyer''.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\nHis ashes were scattered at sea by Ann-Margret, Roger Smith and Martin Menard in front of his former Diamond Head estate on the island of Oahu, Hawaii.\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2017 a documentary about Carr's life was released entitled ''[[The Fabulous Allan Carr]]''.  The director of ''The Fabulous Allan Carr'' [[Jeffrey Schwarz]] said, \"Although it was no secret that Allan Carr was gay, he never formally acknowledged it publicly. The word 'flamboyant' was used to describe him, a code word.\"<ref name=Y/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0139591}}\n* {{Find a Grave|23458|accessdate=September 14, 2010}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9mronRVvdmw The infamous 1989 opening of the Oscars on YouTube]\n* [https://vimeo.com/221448144 The same opening also on Vimeo]\n\n{{Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screenplay 1980\u20132000}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carr, Allan}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:Film producers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Television producers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Jewish American screenwriters]]\n[[Category:LGBT Jews]]\n[[Category:Gay entertainers]]\n[[Category:LGBT businesspeople from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from California]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Illinois]]\n[[Category:American theatre managers and producers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in California]]\n[[Category:Deaths from liver cancer]]\n[[Category:Lake Forest College alumni]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Television producers from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Illinois]]\n[[Category:LGBT producers]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGrease and Broadway success", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allan_Carr"}
{"title_page": "Lakhta Center", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}{{Infobox building\n| name = Lakhta Center\n| native_name = \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\n| native_name_lang = ru\n| former_names = Gazprom Tower, [[Okhta Center]]\n| alternate_names = \n| status = {{Color|green|Completed}}\n| image = Saint Petersburg Lakhta center 06.jpg\n| image_alt = \n| image_size = 280px\n| caption = July 2018\n| location = [[Lakhta, Saint Petersburg|Lakhta]], [[Saint Petersburg]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|59|59|13.7|N|30|10|37.3|E|region:RU|display=inline,title}}\n| address = \n| location_town = \n| location_country = Russia\n| groundbreaking_date = \n| start_date = 2012\n| completion_date = 2019\n| opened_date = \n| inauguration_date = \n| demolition_date = \n| destruction_date = \n| architect = RMJM (until 2011), GORPROJECT\n| landlord = \n| owner = [[Gazprom Neft]]\n| cost = US$1.77 billion<ref>[https://realty.rbc.ru/news/5bed46bd9a794728d6707196]</ref>\n| floor_area = \n| top_floor = \n| floor_count = 87\n| awards = \n| parking = \n| embedded = \n| references = \n| highest_region = \n| highest_reflabel = \n| highest_prev = \n| highest_start = \n| highest_end = \n| highest_next = \n| map_type = \n| map_alt = \n| map_caption = \n| altitude = \n| building_type = \n| architectural_style = \n| structural_system = \n| current_tenants = \n| renovation_date = \n| height = {{convert|462|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| architectural = \n| tip = \n| antenna_spire = \n| roof = \n| observatory = \n| other_dimensions = \n| elevator_count = 40<ref>[https://habr.com/company/lakhtacenter/blog/371087/ Elevators in a skyscraper]</ref>\n| architecture_firm = RMJM (until 2011), GORPROJECT<ref>[https://www.houseandgarden.co.uk/article/europes-tallest-skyscraper-lakhta-centre Europe's tallest skyscraper is nearing completion in St. Petersburg]</ref>\n| main_contractor = [[R\u00f6nesans Holding]]\n| designations = \n| url = \n}}\nThe '''Lakhta Center''' ({{Lang-rus|\u041b\u0430\u0301\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u0301\u043d\u0442\u0440|r=Lakhta tsentr}}) is an 87-story [[skyscraper]] built in the outskirts of [[Lakhta, Saint Petersburg|Lakhta]] in [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russia]]. Standing {{convert|462|m|ft}} tall, the Lakhta Center is the [[List of tallest buildings in Russia|tallest building in Russia]], the [[List of tallest buildings in Europe|tallest building in Europe]], and the [[List of tallest buildings|16th-tallest building in the world]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://skyscrapercenter.com/st.-petersburg/lakhta-center/12575/|title=Lakhta Center - The Skyscraper Center|website=skyscrapercenter.com|access-date=2018-06-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://proektvlahte.ru/ru/about/project/ |title=Lakhta Center Website, \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0446\u0435\u043f\u0446\u0438\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430 |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://proektvlahte.ru/uploaded/file_list/ROSAVIA706(19.07.2011).pdf |title=Federal Air Transport Agency Authorization |date=2011-07-19 |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://skyscrapercenter.com/st.-petersburg/lakhta-center/12575/|title= Lakhta Center|accessdate= 22 January 2014|work= The Skyscraper Center|publisher= [[Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat]]}}</ref> The Lakhta Center is also the second-tallest structure in Russia and Europe, behind [[Ostankino Tower]] in [[Moscow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://skyscrapercenter.com/List/future-tallest-100-buildings|title=Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat, '100 Future tallest buildings in the world'|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723110141/http://skyscrapercenter.com/List/future-tallest-100-buildings|archivedate=2012-07-23|url-status=dead|accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref>\n\nConstruction of Lakhta Center started on 30 October 2012; it was topped out on 29 January 2018.<ref name=\"installation\" >[http://lakhta.center/en/article/?id=1295 The installation of the spire of the Lakhta Center], Press release of 29 January 2018.</ref> The Lakhta Center surpassed Vostok Tower of the [[Federation Tower|Federation Towers]] in Moscow as the tallest building in Russia and Europe on 5 October 2017. The center is designed for large-scale [[mixed-use development]], consisting of public facilities and offices.  The building was designed by [[RMJM]]. The project was then continued by GORPROJECT (2011-2017) based on the RMJM Concept (2011) under the main contractor, [[R\u00f6nesans Holding]]. The Lakhta Center is intended to become the new headquarters of Russian energy company [[Gazprom]].\n\nOn December 24, 2018, Lakhta Center was certified according to the criteria of ecological efficiency at [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] Platinum<ref>[https://www.usgbc.org/projects/lakhta-centertower Lakhta Center-Tower]</ref> \u2013 it is one of the five most eco-friendly skyscrapers in the world.<ref>[https://realty.ria.ru/20191220/1562593482.html The Chronicles of the stone of greens, as buildings become energy efficient]</ref> The concrete pouring of the bottom slab of Lakhta Center's foundation was registered by [[Guinness World Records]] as the largest continuous concrete pour; 19,624 cubic meters of concrete were used, which is approximately 3,000 cubic meters more than in the previous record registered at [[Wilshire Grand Tower]].<ref>[http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/largest-continuous-concrete-pour/ Largest Continuous Concrete Pour]</ref> The tower's [[Curtain wall (architecture)|curtain wall]] is also the world\u2019s largest cold-bent facade by area.\n\nThe opening date of the complex will be determined after the completion of finishing and landscaping. The improvement of the embankments is planned to be completed at the end of 2020.<ref>[https://www.dp.ru/a/2019/08/08/Vozle_Lahti-centra_pojav Near the \"Lakhta center\" will be a public space with \" glass wings\"]</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n=== Planning ===\n\nOn, 26 January 2012, it became known that [[Gazprom]] was planning to build a new harbor for yachts near Lakhta Center and Krestovsky Island. A new company for managing these sea assets was to be created.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/01/26/157/#comments \u0413\u0430\u0437\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043c \u0441\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0438\u0437 \"\u041b\u0435\u043d\u044d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u043e\" \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0440\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044e \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043f\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u044f\u0445\u0442]</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2012, it was announced that a new metro station was to be constructed near Lakhta Center. This metro station's building was included in the City development plan of [[Leningrad]] in 1980 but only with the construction of the Lakhta Center did it again enter the agenda. The plan of the metro station's construction was to be finalized by the end of 2012.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/03/16/074/ \u0412\u044b\u0445\u043e\u0434 \u0438\u0437 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430\" \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d \u0443 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u0413\u0418\u0411\u0414\u0414 16.03.2012 13:26]</ref>\n\nOn 17 August 2012 the permit for construction of the first stage of Lakhta Center, which included a skyscraper and stylobate, was obtained.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/08/20/114/ \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0443\" \u0432\u044b\u0434\u0430\u043d\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0440\u0435\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e]</ref>\nOn 31 August 2012, a public hearing on the topic of the layout and surveying of the site of the Lakhta Center was held in the administration of the Primorsky district of Saint Petersburg. Objects planned for placing in the area of construction, scheme of communications and transportation infrastructure were presented to the public.<ref>[http://izvestia.ru/news/534256 \u041d\u0430 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0448\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f\u0445 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u043b\u0441\u044f \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0434\u0438\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433]</ref>\n\n=== Construction ===\nApproximately 3000 people will be employed in the construction, mostly from professions relating to design and construction. After construction, a few thousand workers of different occupations were expected to be employed in the complex.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2235582|title=\"\u0421\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u043e\u0435\u0442 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u0437\u043c\u043e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0435\u0441\u0441\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0432\"|date=2013-07-17|access-date=2018-06-13}}</ref>\n\nGeodesic, ecologic and soil investigations and design documentation for the project were prepared by GORPROJECT (Russia), NIIOSP (Russia), Petrochim-technologiya LLC (Russia) and Trest GRII JSC (Russia). In planning and executing works at the underground cycle, piling and producing construction materials such companies as [[Arabtec]] (UAE), [[Bauer Group]] (Germany), Geostroy CJSC (Russia), Inforsproekt CJSC (Russia) and Renaissance Construction (Turkey) take part. Verification calculations, working documentation development, optimisation of processes and technical supervision are performed by [[Arup Group Limited]] (Great Britain), [[Samsung C&T]] (Korea) and [[Lend Lease Project Management & Construction]] (Great Britain). Project management is being done by [[AECOM]] (USA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/status/contractors/|title=Key Contractors|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref>\n[http://www.exclusivadesign.com Exclusiva Design] (Italy) is key contractor for the interior design of public spaces.<ref>[http://proektvlahte.ru/en/status/contractors/exclusiva/ Exclusiva Design]</ref><ref>[http://www.exclusivadesign.com/lakhta-center-exclusiva-wins-the-bid-to-design-the-public-spaces/?lang=en/ Lakhta Center: Exclusiva Design wins the Bid to Design the Public Spaces]</ref> German company Josef Gartner is in charge for the glazing of the skyscraper.<ref>[https://www.dp.ru/a/2015/09/16/Nemeckaja_Gartner_otkroet/ \u041d\u0435\u043c\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0430\u044f Gartner \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u043e\u0435\u0442 \u0432 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0437\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043a\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\"]</ref> Glazed facades of Entrance Arch as well as parts of Multi-functional building are done by [[Waagner-Biro]].\n\nOn 30 October 2012 the zero cycle works started. Zero cycle consists of the pit excavation, installation of the disk system, piling under the tower, multifunctional building and stylobate and construction of the foundation itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/status/current/|title= Lakhta Center. Project status|accessdate=2014-08-09}}</ref>\n\n22 April 2014 the main potential general contractor for the construction of Lakhta Center was selected. It was Turkish Renaissance Construction company.<ref>[http://proektvlahte.ru/en/news/?id=237 Potential general constructor selected]</ref> 22 May 2014 the contract for the construction of the foundation of one of the buildings in Lakhta Center was finally signed.\n\n<div>Lakhta Center Construction Time Schedule:</div>\n\n* March 2013 \u2013 zero cycle works are in process. Piles are being installed. According to the schedule of construction a [[diaphragm wall]] is to be completed by the end of April while piling works will continue until 15 August 2013.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/exclusives.asp?id=390991 \u0418\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0434\u0438\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u041e\u0414\u0426 \"\u041e\u0445\u0442\u0430\" \u0410.\u0411\u043e\u0431\u043a\u043e\u0432: \"\u0412 \u201e\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0435\u201c \u0434\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0444\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0434\u043e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043d\u043e-\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0438\u0432\u0430\u044e\u0449\u0435\u0439\"]</ref>\n* July 2013 \u2013 mounting of the 264 piles under the box-type foundation has been finished. Excavation of the foundation pit is in progress.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u043e \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0435] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413160601/http://lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php |date=13 April 2015 }}</ref>\n* September 2013 \u2013 total area of the site is announced to be increased from 330 to 400 thousand square meters due to a 700 parking space expansion to the planned parking spaces.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://restate.ru/material/152481.html |title=\u0421\u0422\u0420\u041e\u0418\u0422\u0415\u041b\u042c\u0421\u0422\u0412\u041e \u041d\u0423\u041b\u0415\u0412\u041e\u0413\u041e \u0426\u0418\u041a\u041b\u0410 \"\u041b\u0410\u0425\u0422\u0410 \u0426\u0415\u041d\u0422\u0420\u0410\" \u041e\u0426\u0415\u041d\u0418\u041b\u0418 \u0412 $100 \u041c\u041b\u041d |access-date=26 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128003246/http://restate.ru/material/152481.html |archive-date=28 January 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* October 2013 \u2013 construction of box-type foundation has been started. According to the plan this part of the work is to be finished in 2014.<ref>[http://advis.ru/php/view_news.php?id=763315EE-9CD4-6040-80D4-FA160CE9C441 \u0420\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u044b \u043d\u0443\u043b\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043f\u043b\u043e\u0449\u0430\u0434\u043a\u0435 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\".]</ref>\n\n* December 2013 \u2013 mounting of the concrete disks to the [[diaphragm wall]] has started. Disks are to provide the diaphragm wall with more resistance to outside ground pressure.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rcmm.ru/content/topics/428.html |title=\u041d\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0431 \u0443 \u0424\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0432\u0430. |access-date=10 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317210545/http://rcmm.ru/content/topics/428.html |archive-date=17 March 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* April 2014 \u2013 construction of foundation pit for the skyscraper is over.<ref>[http://karpovka.net/2014/04/02/137579/ \u0413\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u043a\u043e\u0442\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u043d\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0430 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\"]</ref>\n* June 2014 \u2013 piling is completed. 264 piles were mounted for the tower of Lakhta Center, 848 piles were mounted for the mixed-use building and entrance arch and 968 piles were mounted for the stylobate (undergroung parking). All in all 2080 piles were dug in.<ref>[http://proektvlahte.ru/en/article/?id=892 All 2080 Piles in Lakhta Center Foundation]</ref>\n* September 2014 \u2013 excavation of the foundation pit for the mixed-use building has been finished. Foundation concreting has started.\n* February and March 2015 \u2013 the pouring of the bottom slab of the skyscraper's box shaped foundation over. 19,624 cubic meters of concrete were cast in the foundation.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.fontanka.ru/2015/03/02/169/ Alexey Miller: First floors of the skyscraper in Lakhta will appear this year]</ref>\n* June 2015 \u2013 construction of the underground floors has finished.\n* September 2015 \u2013 pouring of the 2m thick upper box foundation slab has been completed, which means that all works below zero elevation are finished.\n* September 2015 \u2013 the construction of the first floors of the tower core is underway.<ref>[http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/article/?id=1087 Pouring of the Upper Slab of the Lakhta Center Tower Foundation]</ref>\n* January 2016 \u2013 construction of the succeeding ten floors of the tower; works on stylobate complex.\n* April 2016 \u2013 construction of the tower core at floors 22-26. Installation of the metal farm in the 18-22nd floors of the tower.\n* May 2016 \u2013 glazing of the facade of the Tower has started.\n* September 2016 \u2013 construction of the tower core at floors 46-50.<ref>[https://www.liebherr.com/en/deu/latest-news/news-press-releases/detail/liebherr-tower-cranes-in-action-erecting-the-highest-building-in-europe.html?news.type=press/ Liebherr tower cranes in action erecting the highest building in Europe]</ref>\n* December 2016 \u2013 installation of facade at floors 16-18; construction of the tower core at floors 57-61 \n* February 2017 \u2013 Lahkta Center's tower reaches height of 260 metres; floors 61-64 are under construction.\n* April 2017 -  height exceeds 300 meters, making Lakhta Center a [[supertall]] building (international classification), work is being done on the 67 floor.\n* May 2017 - the skyscraper reached the height 327,6 meters, working on the 78th floor.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2017/05/13/034/ Lakhta Center outgrew the tower]</ref>\n* August 2017 - Installation of the spire starts at 83 floors.\n* 5 October 2017 - Lakhta center became the tallest building in Europe when it reached a height of 374 meters.<ref>[http://lakhta.center/en/article/?id=1280 European altitude record broken]</ref><ref>[http://www.euronews.com/2017/10/06/russian-skyscraper-becomes-europe-s-tallest-building# Russian skyscraper \u2018becomes Europe\u2019s tallest building]</ref>\n* 29 January 2018 - the height of Lakhta center project reached a height of 462 meters, the assembly of structures of the spire is completed. The glazing of the tower continues at floor 70.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6Y-0SYU5sJU Lakhta Center reached the design height]</ref>\n* On 27 June 2018, the initial commissioning of the building was carried out. Technical documentation, building plan and technical passport were prepared.<ref>[https://www.archdaily.com/898132/europes-tallest-skyscraper-approaches-completion-in-st-petersburg Europe's Tallest Skyscraper Approaches Completion in St Petersburg]</ref>\n* On 16 October 2018, Lakhta Center MFC JSC received authorization for commissioning of the facility. The relevant document was officially published by the State Construction Supervision and Inspection Service of Saint Petersburg, Russia. There is about a year to go until the opening of Lakhta Center Multifunctional Complex, its dominant being the tallest skyscraper of Europe.<ref>[https://lakhta.center/en/article/?id=1321 Lakhta Center Officially Commissioned]</ref>\n\nNext to the already commissioned Lakhta Center, construction continues. To the four objects of the complex (tower, multi-purpose building, arch, stylobate) will be added one more. According to official documents, it takes place under the name \"Complex of buildings and structures\", or simply KZS.<ref>[https://www.fontanka.ru/2019/03/28/111/ \"Complex of buildings and structures\"]</ref>\n\nThe complex of buildings and structures is a single building consisting of two buildings connected by a courtyard. The authors of the project suggest that it will not only strengthen the office function of the Lakhta Center, but also complete the formation of the architectural ensemble, balancing the skyscraper in the horizontal.<ref>[https://www.the-village.ru/village/city/news-city/345989-kzs-lahta \"Complex of buildings and structures\". It will be built at the \"Lakhta center\" in 2021]</ref> The total area of the Lakhta center is 400 000 m\u00b2. With the addition of the KZS, the total area of the complex is 570 000 m\u00b2.<ref>[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/news.asp?id=924846&sec=1679 \u041a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u043a\u0440\u0443\u0433 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442 Renaissance Construction]</ref>\n\n== Multi-functional building ==\nMulti-functional building (MFZ) - an object divided into two buildings - North and South, which are United by a common Foundation, stylobate and roof. The building resembles a boomerang. It has a variable number of storeys with a height difference from 7 to 17 floors, with the peak height being a little more than 80 meters. The building is approximately 300 meters long.  Feature - negative angle of the end facades due to the removal of the console on 25 m. Facades - glass, with a total area of more than 60 thousand m2.<ref>[https://habr.com/ru/company/lakhtacenter/blog/371535/ Horizontal versus vertical. Or for? Why Lakhta Center \"recumbent\" dominant]</ref>\n\nConstructive scheme of the building - frame. More than 24 thousand tons of metal structures were used for the construction of this facility.\n\nThe main load-bearing elements are 4 reinforced concrete cores which perceive horizontal and vertical loadings, transferring them to the base executed in the form of the plate grillage leaning against piles. Between the Southern and Northern buildings of the MFZ along the entire height of the atrium, with a roof of translucent polymer membranes ETFE. In the space of the atrium, transitional bridges are spanned, which serve as observation points. Atrium is a pedestrian area from which you can get to any of the objects of the building.\n\nThe MFZ will house a number of public spaces - for example, a planetarium in the shape of a ball or a seven-storey hall-transformer, which can take different configurations: from the classical parquet to the amphitheater.\n\n== Design ==\n\n=== Facilities ===\nLakhta Center will contain offices, a [[co-working]] center, a sports center, a children's science center, and a conference center. Lakhta Center's project includes 1,500 square meters of indoor exhibition space. Part of the open area will be used to demonstrate objects of art, installations and sculptures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/ru/press/gallery/presentation/?id=445|title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044b {{!}} \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u2013 \u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0444\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u0432 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0435 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430|website=www.proektvlahte.ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref> There will be a free public observation deck at the top of the skyscraper at the height of 357m.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/about/objects/viewpoint/|title=Observation deck {{!}} \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u2013 \u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0444\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u0432 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0435 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430|website=www.proektvlahte.ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2014/08/19/122/|script-title=ru:\u0421\u043c\u043e\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0443\u044e \u043f\u043b\u043e\u0449\u0430\u0434\u043a\u0443 \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0434\u0443\u044e\u0442 \u0446\u0438\u0444\u0440\u043e\u0432\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0430\u043c\u0438|date=2014-08-19|accessdate=2018-07-30|language=ru}}</ref> Planetarium - a 19-meter sparkling ball on the surface of which 1223 curved triangular stainless steel sheet, polished to a Shine. The most accurate projection of the starry sky is formed by a star machine (Japanese projector - Ohira Tech Megastar-IIA ), and larger objects, artificial aircraft, visual effects and much more \u2013 digital, created by a projection system with a resolution of 8K Meridian, which uses 10 laser 4K projectors SONY GTZ280. Five projectors illuminate the lower tier of the dome, four \u2013 the top, and one forms an image at the Zenith. Thus, the total resolution in 48 483 533 pixels.<ref>[https://habr.com/ru/company/lakhtacenter/blog/447764/ \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e \u043a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0441! \u041a\u0430\u043a \u0443\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043d \u043f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430]</ref>\n\n=== Features ===\n\n* The main entrance of Lakhta Center is designed to be an [[arch]]. The height of the arch is almost 24m while its length is 98m.\n* There will be 34 elevators in the tower, but not all of them will travel to the top floor. The mixed-use building will contain 62 elevators. Besides these elevators there will be special firefighter lifts constructed to be used in case of emergency. The total capacity of all elevators is up to 1,280 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nvspb.ru/stories/neboskreby-menyayut-soznanie-sociuma-52309|title=\"\u041d\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0451\u0431\u044b \u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f\u044e\u0442 \u0441\u043e\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u043e\u0446\u0438\u0443\u043c\u0430\" {{!}} \u041d\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u044f|website=www.nvspb.ru|language=ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref>\n* Lakhta Center's foundation is going to be concreted continuously in round-the-clock mode. Constructors plan to pour 24,000 cubic metres in 48 hours. The volume of concrete to be poured under the mixed-use building near the tower is 48,000 cubic metres. This volume is large enough to be included in the [[Guinness Book of Records]].<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/exclusives.asp?id=447425 Construction director of Lakhta Center Elena Morozova: \"We will become record-holders due to the volume of concrete poured\"]</ref>\n* Around 400,000 cubic meters of concrete will be used for Lakhta Center's construction. During the first stage of foundation concreting 8,500 cubic meters of concrete will be used.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dp.ru/a/2014/12/08/Beton_dlja_Lahta_Centra/|title=\u0412 \u0441\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435 \u0434\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0431\u0440\u044f \u043d\u0430\u0447\u043d\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u0444\u0443\u043d\u0434\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\"|website=www.dp.ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref>\n* The area of glazing of the Tower totals 72,500 square meters as the area of the glazing for the complex in the whole makes up 130,000 square meters.<ref>[http://www.megapolis-online.ru/articles/intervyu/lahta-centr-462-metra-nad-urovnem-morya-1.html \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440. 462 \u043c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0434 \u0443\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0435\u043c \u043c\u043e\u0440\u044f]</ref>\n* Lakhta Center is designed to a high safety standard, which allows it to stand on one core even if all ten supportive columns collapse. The core structure is up to the highest fire rating. The building is designed to be able to withstand a four-hour fire without any structural damage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.popmech.ru/technologies/48791-kak-stroitsya-lakhta-tsentr-v-sankt-peterburge/#full|script-title=ru:\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0441\u044f \u00ab\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u00bb \u0432 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435|work=Popmech.ru|access-date=2018-07-30|language=ru-RU}}</ref>\n* On December 31, 2018 [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qlwYShApM9U Green Christmas lights] were lit on the skyscraper, thus turning the building into the highest Christmas tree in Europe<ref>[https://forpost-sz.ru/a/2018-12-31/lakhta-centr-prevratili-v-samuyu-vysokuyu-yolku-evropy The tallest Christmas tree in Europe]</ref>\n* On June 28, 2019, an automatic weather station was installed at the highest point of the spire (462 meters), which monitors temperature, humidity, wind direction and speed.<ref>[https://www.fontanka.ru/2019/06/28/053/ From Lakhta Center will now monitor the weather. On the spire of the St. Petersburg skyscraper appeared weather station]</ref>\n* 2019 - the Lakhta center complex became the leader in the number of nominations for the Award of Excellence and Urban Habitat.<ref>[https://tallinnovation.com/program/projects-featured/ Award of Excellence Winners]</ref> It was a finalist in five categories: Best high-rise building of 400 meters and higher; Construction award; Award in the field of construction engineering; award in the field of geotechnical engineering; award for facade engineering.\n\n=== Innovations ===\nIn order to provide more effective fire-fighting, a HI-FOG water mist suppression system will be used. When the temperature exceeds 57&nbsp;\u00b0C, sprinklers creating a water mist will start working automatically. Along with the sprinklers, there will be drenchers which could be switched on manually or by the means of remote control in order to create a water curtain in an emergency.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php#101 \u041c\u041e \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u041e\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e \u041e\u0431 \u0438\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u0432 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0435\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427193513/http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php#101 |date=27 April 2017 }}</ref> Lakhta Center is also set to be the first skyscraper in St. Petersburg where an ice formation control system will be used. Heating of the glass at high floors will prevent ice accumulation and help maintain good visibility. The spire of the Tower will be made from metal gauze to prevent a layer of ice forming in winter.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=6 \u041c\u041e \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u041e\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e. \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440: \u043b\u0435\u0434 \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0440\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043c] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427193302/http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=6 |date=27 April 2017 }}</ref> The consumption of material and energy resources will be decreased due to conversion of kinetic energy of the Center's workers and visitors' steps to electric energy.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.regnum.ru/news/realestate/1784199.html \"\u0417\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\" \u0432 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435: \u044d\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0438\u044f \u0448\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0432 \u043e\u0441\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0442 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\"]</ref>\nDuring migration periods of birds special illumination will be used to light the tower.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.gazeta.ru/realty/2015/05/06_a_6668381.shtml Lakhta Center Skyscraper Continues to Surprise with its Technologies]</ref>\n\n=== Environmental technologies ===\nWhile designing Lakhta Center several \"green\" and energy-saving technologies were planned for further application. They are\n\n* Double facade. Usage of double glazing will help to increase the level of thermal insulation, which allowed the designers to reduce costs for heating and conditioning.\n* Usage of the excess heat generated by working technical equipment for the heating of premises.\n* Usage of equipment with reduced noise level along with noise suppressors, sound-proof curtain walls and [[floating floor]]s.\n* Usage of economical infrared radiators.\n* Usage of contactless sensors or [[motion detectors]] for economizing electric energy and water.\n* Mounting of the systems supporting the optimal level of temperature and humidity inside the building.\n* Smart waste disposal system which improves hygiene and reduces CO2 emissions. Also wastes are sorted, which is one of the essential principles of green construction. Waste disposal is required by 20 times less frequent than in a conventional system.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.megapolis-online.com/articles/intervyu/lahta-centr-462-metra-nad-urovnem-morya-1.html Lakhta Center: 462 meters above the sea level] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170208073228/http://www.megapolis-online.com/articles/intervyu/lahta-centr-462-metra-nad-urovnem-morya-1.html |date=8 February 2017 }}</ref>\n* Constructing of the ice storages which will accumulate up to 1000 tons of ice at night for air conditioning during the daytime. It will help to reduce the differences in the usage of electricity during the night and day periods. It also allows reducing expenditures on electric power on the account of the differences in tariffs for day and night usage of electricity. As the cooling of the building is to be made using accumulative ice generators it will be possible to save on electricity expenditures up to 13 thousand rubles a day.\n* In support to the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] and FLAP's (Fatal Light Awareness Program) \"Bird - Friendly Building Program\", Lakhta Center's illumination will be designed so to make the building bird-safe especially in the periods of migration of birds (autumn, winter). The system of the illumination intensity and color change is under development at the moment.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=lakhta-tsentr-stremitsya-podruzhitsya-s-ptitsami Lakhta Center is eager to make friends with birds] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428052153/http://old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=lakhta-tsentr-stremitsya-podruzhitsya-s-ptitsami |date=28 April 2017 }}</ref>\n* Due to the peculiarities of the highly humid and windy climate in the North Western region of Russia the possibility of icing up of buildings is relatively high. In order to prevent complete icing up of the spire of the Lakhta Center's tower engineers changed glassing to the metal gauze.<ref>[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/news.asp?id=544242&sec=1671 \u0421\u043f\u0435\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0433\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044b \u043f\u043e\u0437\u0432\u043e\u043b\u044f\u0442 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0443\" \u044d\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0434\u043e 13 \u0442\u044b\u0441. \u0440\u0443\u0431. \u0432 \u0441\u0443\u0442\u043a\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u044d\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0440\u043e\u044d\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0438\u0438]</ref>\n* In order to provide Lakhta Center and adjoining areas with electricity without making any extra burden on existing infrastructure a new standalone power substation \"Nevskaya guba\" will be constructed.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://asninfo.ru/news/v-lahte-postroyat-podstanciyu-nevskaya-guba \"Nevskaya guba\" power substation will be built in Lakhta]</ref>\n\nAll in all, while constructing Lakhta Center approximately 100 [[innovation]]s are to be used. It lets increase the indexes of energy saving by 40% compared to the buildings where standard technologies are in use.\n\nIn experts' opinion, period of recoupment of using green and energy-saving technologies in Lakhta Center may be at about 20 years though Lakhta Center's Projection department's specialists think that this figure is a bit overestimated.\n\n===Transportation development===\nLakhta Center's construction raises a problem of transportation development because of the expected growth of the traffic flow in the region. Two traffic circles are to be built near Lakhta Center. These will become part of the \u041c32\u0410 highway in the future.<ref>[http://www.spbdnevnik.ru/news/2014-07-10/dva-razvorotnykh-koltsa-poyavyatsya-v-primorskom-rayone/]</ref>\nA light rail service from [[Finland Railway Station]] and a new tram line from Primorskaya underground station will be built to serve Lakhta Center. Plans are ongoing to build a new underground station with the working title of \"Lakhta\".<ref>[http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/about/transport/ Transport Infrastructure Development]</ref> Bicycle lanes near Lakhta Center with 90 parking places for bicycles are also planned.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2014/07/15/138/ \u0412 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u044f\u0437\u043a\u0438 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u044b \u041c-32 \u0438 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0448\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0443\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u0438 \u0432\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u043a\u0443]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/obshchestvennye-slushaniya-.php |title=\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0448\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f |access-date=18 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413143303/http://lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/obshchestvennye-slushaniya-.php |archive-date=13 April 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\nAs the [[Historic Centre of Saint Petersburg and Related Groups of Monuments|historical center of St. Petersburg]] has become a [[World Heritage Site]] since 1990; The [[World Heritage Committee]] opposed the construction of the 400-metre tower of [[Okhta Center]] as it would affect the cityscape of historic Saint Petersburg.<ref>[https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/612 UNESCO welcomes backing by President of Russian Federation for the preservation of St Petersburg]</ref> In December 2006 [[UNESCO]] World Heritage Centre Director Francesco Bandarin reminded Russia about its obligations to preserve it and expressed concern over the project.<ref>[http://www.vedomosti.ru/newspaper/article.shtml?2006/12/05/117081 UNESCO is worried] by Elena Ragozina, [[Vedomosti]] #229 (1756), 5 December 2006 (in Russian).</ref> In 2007, the [[World Monuments Fund]] placed the historic skyline of St. Petersburg on its 2008 Watch List of 100 Most Endangered Sites due to the potential construction of the building, and in 2009 reported that the tower \"would damage the image of Russia.\"<ref name=BBCUNESCO>{{Cite news |title=Russian tower plans cause alarm |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8272401.stm |publisher=BBC News |date=2009-09-23 |accessdate=2009-10-12}}</ref> During the 36 session of the World Heritage Committee of UNESCO held in Saint Petersburg in 2012 it was stated that a large area of Saint-Petersburg falls within preservation and buffer zones provided for UNESCO World Heritage Sites. That is why it is good for the city that the Okhta Center, which had been planned by Gazprom in front of Smolny Cathedral was moved to Lakhta.<ref>[https://whc.unesco.org/en/sessions/36COM 36th session of the Committee of the World Heritage Committee]</ref> Eleonora Mitrofanova, Permanent Representative of the Russian Federation to UNESCO noticed that the approved construction project for Lakhta Center is located far from the buffer zone and the historical center, so in theory Gazprom is not even obliged to ask UNESCO. However, the government authorities will definitely have consultations for the project with UNESCO. Now we are working to clarify the boundaries of the World Heritage zone and the boundaries of the buffer zone.<ref>[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/news.asp?id=326845&sec=1671 \u0412\u044b\u0441\u043e\u0442\u043a\u0430 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0442 \u043f\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0440\u0430\u043c\u0443 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430 \u0441\u043e \u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0424\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0432\u0430 \u2014 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434 \u0420\u0424 \u0432 \u042e\u041d\u0415\u0421\u041a\u041e]</ref>\n\nThe project being moved to Lakhta didn't stop the discussions. On 11 April 2012, ex-governor of St. Petersburg and now Federation Council chairwoman Valentina Matvienko said to journalists that the \"Lakhta center could become a new symbol of the city and attract the businessmen from all over the world to St. Petersburg.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo.msk.ru/programs/sorokina/876139-echo/ |title=\"In the light circle\", the interview with Ms.Matvienko at \"Echo Moskvy\" |publisher=Echo.msk.ru |date= |accessdate=2012-10-28}}</ref>\n\nDuring his visit to Russia in 2011 the Chairman of the [[Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat]] Professor Sang-Dae Kim was treated to a presentation of a project of Lakhta Center. Professor Kim commented on the \"modern shape\" of the proposed Lakhta Center, which according to him had \"nothing in common with ordinary boxes\".<ref>[http://www.ctbuh.org/Events/ToursVisits/ProfKimVisitstoSEAsiaRussia/ProfKimvisitRussia/tabid/2778/language/en-US/Default.aspx CTBUH Meeting: Russia]</ref> He also stated that something new ought to be created, which can be shown to new generations in 200\u2013300 years as for them what is created nowadays will be the same history as the architecture of the 18-19th centuries for us today. Professor also noticed that the project reminds him of an oriental concept [[Yin Yang]]: on the one hand, the historic part of the city with horizontal buildings and water, and on the other hand, a vertical which will add additional charm to the city. Lakhta Center combines an interesting form and modern technologies, so up to Mr. Kim, with the lapse of time the Center can become a new symbol of Saint Petersburg.<ref>[http://www.gazeta.ru/realty/2011/09/07_a_3759709.shtml Without skyscrapers Russia is the Kremlin and the Red Army]</ref>\n\nOn 16 May 2012, St. Petersburg governor Georgiy Poltavchenko emphasized in his annual report for House of Assembly the necessity of building a new \"city\" in St. Petersburg. According to Mr Poltavchenko, there are three appropriate districts for that: Lakhta center, Pulkovo and [[aggradation|aggradated]] territories near Waterfront.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/05/15/056/ |title=Poltavchenko: Petersburg needs a new business center and town-planning dictation |publisher=Fontanka.ru |date=2012-05-15 |accessdate=2012-10-28}}</ref>\n\n==Construction gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Site's view prior to construction.jpg|Site's view prior to construction, July 2012.\nFile:Aerial view of the construction site of Lakhta Center in Saint Petersburg, November 2014.jpg|Panoramic view of the construction site, November 2014.\nFile:Piling process.jpg|Piling process\nFile:Construction of the foundation under the Tower.jpg|Construction of the foundation under the Tower\nFile:Foundations of the Tower and mixed-use building are ready.jpg|Foundations of the tower and mixed-use building are ready\nFile:Lakhta Center.jpg|Lakhta Center. Nov, 2015\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0444\u0435\u0432\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c 2016).jpg|Lakhta Center. Feb, 2016\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0438\u044e\u043b\u044c 2016).jpg|Lakhta Center. Jul, 2016\nFile:Lakhta_Center_Oktober_2016.jpg|The state of the construction as of October, 2016\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043d\u043e\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c 2016).jpg|Lakhta Center. Nov, 2016\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0434\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0431\u0440\u044c 2016).jpg|Skyscraper at the end of 2016. Height is 245 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u043b\u044c 2017).jpg|Skyscraper in April 2017. Height is 310 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043c\u0430\u0439 2017).jpg|Lakhta Center in May 2017. Height is 323 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0441\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c 2017).jpg|Lakhta Center in September 2017. Height is 365 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440, \u044f\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044c 2018 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430.jpg|Lakhta Center in January 2018. Installation of the spire, height of about 450 meters\nFile:Lakhta Center orig.jpg|Skyscraper at the end of February 2018. Installation of the spire is complete, glazing of the tower and spire continues.\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043c\u0430\u044f\u043a).jpg|Lakhta Center in May 2018.\nFile:Das Lachta Zentr- \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 2H1A5980WI.jpg| June 2018\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043d\u043e\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c 2018).jpg|Lakhta Center in November 2018\nFile:2-\u044f \u043e\u0447\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u044c \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430.jpg|Construction of the 2nd stage (November 2018)\nFile:Lakhta Center at night in april 2019.jpg|April 2019\nFile:\u041d\u043e\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0444\u0430\u0441\u0430\u0434\u044b \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430.jpg|Skyscraper lighting\nFile:Lakhta Center, spire.jpg|The spire of the skyscraper (General view).\nFile:\u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445 \u0448\u043f\u0438\u043b\u044f \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430.jpg|The top of the spire. Floodlight projectors are integrated in it\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of tallest buildings in Russia]]\n*[[List of tallest buildings in Europe]]\n* [[List of twisted buildings]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/ Official site of Lakhta Center]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070401024640/http://www.ohta-center.ru/ Official Site of the Okhta Center project]\n* [http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/future/view/ Visual Analysis projecting the appearance of the tower at the Lakhta site, from various points in St. Petersburg]\n* [https://ru-ru.facebook.com/lakhtacenter.ru/ Official social media page]\n\n{{Supertall skyscrapers}}\n\n[[Category:Saint Petersburg culture]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Saint Petersburg]]\n[[Category:Architecture of Russia]]\n[[Category:Gazprom]]\n[[Category:Skyscrapers in Russia]]\n[[Category:Twisted buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures under construction in Russia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}{{Infobox building\n| name = Lakhta Center\n| native_name = \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\n| native_name_lang = ru\n| former_names = Gazprom Tower, [[Okhta Center]]\n| alternate_names = \n| status = {{Color|green|Completed}}\n| image = Saint Petersburg Lakhta center 06.jpg\n| image_alt = \n| image_size = 280px\n| caption = July 2018\n| location = [[Lakhta, Saint Petersburg|Lakhta]], [[Saint Petersburg]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|59|59|13.7|N|30|10|37.3|E|region:RU|display=inline,title}}\n| address = \n| location_town = \n| location_country = Russia\n| groundbreaking_date = \n| start_date = 2012\n| completion_date = 2019\n| opened_date = \n| inauguration_date = \n| demolition_date = \n| destruction_date = \n| architect = RMJM (until 2011), GORPROJECT\n| landlord = \n| owner = [[Gazprom Neft]]\n| cost = US$1.77 billion<ref>[https://realty.rbc.ru/news/5bed46bd9a794728d6707196]</ref>\n| floor_area = \n| top_floor = \n| floor_count = 87\n| awards = \n| parking = \n| embedded = \n| references = \n| highest_region = \n| highest_reflabel = \n| highest_prev = \n| highest_start = \n| highest_end = \n| highest_next = \n| map_type = \n| map_alt = \n| map_caption = \n| altitude = \n| building_type = \n| architectural_style = \n| structural_system = \n| current_tenants = \n| renovation_date = \n| height = {{convert|462|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| architectural = \n| tip = \n| antenna_spire = \n| roof = \n| observatory = \n| other_dimensions = \n| elevator_count = 40<ref>[https://habr.com/company/lakhtacenter/blog/371087/ Elevators in a skyscraper]</ref>\n| architecture_firm = RMJM (until 2011), GORPROJECT<ref>[https://www.houseandgarden.co.uk/article/europes-tallest-skyscraper-lakhta-centre Europe's tallest skyscraper is nearing completion in St. Petersburg]</ref>\n| main_contractor = [[R\u00f6nesans Holding]]\n| designations = \n| url = \n}}\nThe '''Lakhta Center''' ({{Lang-rus|\u041b\u0430\u0301\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u0301\u043d\u0442\u0440|r=Lakhta tsentr}}) is an 87-story [[skyscraper]] built in the outskirts of [[Lakhta, Saint Petersburg|Lakhta]] in [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russia]]. Standing {{convert|462|m|ft}} tall, the Lakhta Center is the [[List of tallest buildings in Russia|tallest building in Russia]], the [[List of tallest buildings in Europe|tallest building in Europe]], and the [[List of tallest buildings|16th-tallest building in the world]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://skyscrapercenter.com/st.-petersburg/lakhta-center/12575/|title=Lakhta Center - The Skyscraper Center|website=skyscrapercenter.com|access-date=2018-06-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://proektvlahte.ru/ru/about/project/ |title=Lakhta Center Website, \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0446\u0435\u043f\u0446\u0438\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430 |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://proektvlahte.ru/uploaded/file_list/ROSAVIA706(19.07.2011).pdf |title=Federal Air Transport Agency Authorization |date=2011-07-19 |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://skyscrapercenter.com/st.-petersburg/lakhta-center/12575/|title= Lakhta Center|accessdate= 22 January 2014|work= The Skyscraper Center|publisher= [[Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat]]}}</ref> The Lakhta Center is also the second-tallest structure in Russia and Europe, behind [[Ostankino Tower]] in [[Moscow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://skyscrapercenter.com/List/future-tallest-100-buildings|title=Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat, '100 Future tallest buildings in the world'|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723110141/http://skyscrapercenter.com/List/future-tallest-100-buildings|archivedate=2012-07-23|url-status=dead|accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref>\n\nConstruction of Lakhta Center started on 30 October 2012; it was topped out on 29 January 2018.<ref name=\"installation\" >[http://lakhta.center/en/article/?id=1295 The installation of the spire of the Lakhta Center], Press release of 29 January 2018.</ref> The Lakhta Center surpassed Vostok Tower of the [[Federation Tower|Federation Towers]] in Moscow as the tallest building in Russia and Europe on 5 October 2017. The center is designed for large-scale [[mixed-use development]], consisting of public facilities and offices.  The building was designed by [[RMJM]]. The project was then continued by GORPROJECT (2011-2017) based on the RMJM Concept (2011) under the main contractor, [[R\u00f6nesans Holding]]. The Lakhta Center is intended to become the new headquarters of Russian energy company [[Gazprom]].\n\nOn December 24, 2018, Lakhta Center was certified according to the criteria of ecological efficiency at [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] Platinum<ref>[https://www.usgbc.org/projects/lakhta-centertower Lakhta Center-Tower]</ref> \u2013 it is one of the five most eco-friendly skyscrapers in the world.<ref>[https://realty.ria.ru/20191220/1562593482.html The Chronicles of the stone of greens, as buildings become energy efficient]</ref> The concrete pouring of the bottom slab of Lakhta Center's foundation was registered by [[Guinness World Records]] as the largest continuous concrete pour; 19,624 cubic meters of concrete were used, which is approximately 3,000 cubic meters more than in the previous record registered at [[Wilshire Grand Tower]].<ref>[http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/largest-continuous-concrete-pour/ Largest Continuous Concrete Pour]</ref> The tower's [[Curtain wall (architecture)|curtain wall]] is also the world\u2019s largest cold-bent facade by area.\n\nThe opening date of the complex will be determined after the completion of finishing and landscaping. The improvement of the embankments is planned to be completed at the end of 2020.<ref>[https://www.dp.ru/a/2019/08/08/Vozle_Lahti-centra_pojav Near the \"Lakhta center\" will be a public space with \" glass wings\"]</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n=== Planning ===\n\nOn, 26 January 2012, it became known that [[Gazprom]] was planning to build a new harbor for yachts near Lakhta Center and Krestovsky Island. A new company for managing these sea assets was to be created.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/01/26/157/#comments \u0413\u0430\u0437\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043c \u0441\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0438\u0437 \"\u041b\u0435\u043d\u044d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u043e\" \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0440\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044e \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043f\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u044f\u0445\u0442]</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2012, it was announced that a new metro station was to be constructed near Lakhta Center. This metro station's building was included in the City development plan of [[Leningrad]] in 1980 but only with the construction of the Lakhta Center did it again enter the agenda. The plan of the metro station's construction was to be finalized by the end of 2012.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/03/16/074/ \u0412\u044b\u0445\u043e\u0434 \u0438\u0437 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430\" \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d \u0443 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u0413\u0418\u0411\u0414\u0414 16.03.2012 13:26]</ref>\n\nOn 17 August 2012 the permit for construction of the first stage of Lakhta Center, which included a skyscraper and stylobate, was obtained.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/08/20/114/ \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0443\" \u0432\u044b\u0434\u0430\u043d\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0440\u0435\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e]</ref>\nOn 31 August 2012, a public hearing on the topic of the layout and surveying of the site of the Lakhta Center was held in the administration of the Primorsky district of Saint Petersburg. Objects planned for placing in the area of construction, scheme of communications and transportation infrastructure were presented to the public.<ref>[http://izvestia.ru/news/534256 \u041d\u0430 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0448\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f\u0445 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u043b\u0441\u044f \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0434\u0438\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433]</ref>\n\n=== Construction ===\nApproximately 3000 people will be employed in the construction, mostly from professions relating to design and construction. After construction, a few thousand workers of different occupations were expected to be employed in the complex.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2235582|title=\"\u0421\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u043e\u0435\u0442 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u0437\u043c\u043e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0435\u0441\u0441\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0432\"|date=2013-07-17|access-date=2018-06-13}}</ref>\n\nGeodesic, ecologic and soil investigations and design documentation for the project were prepared by GORPROJECT (Russia), NIIOSP (Russia), Petrochim-technologiya LLC (Russia) and Trest GRII JSC (Russia). In planning and executing works at the underground cycle, piling and producing construction materials such companies as [[Arabtec]] (UAE), [[Bauer Group]] (Germany), Geostroy CJSC (Russia), Inforsproekt CJSC (Russia) and Renaissance Construction (Turkey) take part. Verification calculations, working documentation development, optimisation of processes and technical supervision are performed by [[Arup Group Limited]] (Great Britain), [[Samsung C&T]] (Korea) and [[Lend Lease Project Management & Construction]] (Great Britain). Project management is being done by [[AECOM]] (USA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/status/contractors/|title=Key Contractors|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref>\n[http://www.exclusivadesign.com Exclusiva Design] (Italy) is key contractor for the interior design of public spaces.<ref>[http://proektvlahte.ru/en/status/contractors/exclusiva/ Exclusiva Design]</ref><ref>[http://www.exclusivadesign.com/lakhta-center-exclusiva-wins-the-bid-to-design-the-public-spaces/?lang=en/ Lakhta Center: Exclusiva Design wins the Bid to Design the Public Spaces]</ref> German company Josef Gartner is in charge for the glazing of the skyscraper.<ref>[https://www.dp.ru/a/2015/09/16/Nemeckaja_Gartner_otkroet/ \u041d\u0435\u043c\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0430\u044f Gartner \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u043e\u0435\u0442 \u0432 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0437\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043a\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\"]</ref> Glazed facades of Entrance Arch as well as parts of Multi-functional building are done by [[Waagner-Biro]].\n\nOn 30 October 2012 the zero cycle works started. Zero cycle consists of the pit excavation, installation of the disk system, piling under the tower, multifunctional building and stylobate and construction of the foundation itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/status/current/|title= Lakhta Center. Project status|accessdate=2014-08-09}}</ref>\n\n22 April 2014 the main potential general contractor for the construction of Lakhta Center was selected. It was Turkish Renaissance Construction company.<ref>[http://proektvlahte.ru/en/news/?id=237 Potential general constructor selected]</ref> 22 May 2014 the contract for the construction of the foundation of one of the buildings in Lakhta Center was finally signed.\n\n<div>Lakhta Center Construction Time Schedule:</div>\n\n* March 2013 \u2013 zero cycle works are in process. Piles are being installed. According to the schedule of construction a [[diaphragm wall]] is to be completed by the end of April while piling works will continue until 15 August 2013.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/exclusives.asp?id=390991 \u0418\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0434\u0438\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u041e\u0414\u0426 \"\u041e\u0445\u0442\u0430\" \u0410.\u0411\u043e\u0431\u043a\u043e\u0432: \"\u0412 \u201e\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0435\u201c \u0434\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0444\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0434\u043e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043d\u043e-\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0438\u0432\u0430\u044e\u0449\u0435\u0439\"]</ref>\n* July 2013 \u2013 mounting of the 264 piles under the box-type foundation has been finished. Excavation of the foundation pit is in progress.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u043e \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0435] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413160601/http://lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php |date=13 April 2015 }}</ref>\n* September 2013 \u2013 total area of the site is announced to be increased from 330 to 400 thousand square meters due to a 700 parking space expansion to the planned parking spaces.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://restate.ru/material/152481.html |title=\u0421\u0422\u0420\u041e\u0418\u0422\u0415\u041b\u042c\u0421\u0422\u0412\u041e \u041d\u0423\u041b\u0415\u0412\u041e\u0413\u041e \u0426\u0418\u041a\u041b\u0410 \"\u041b\u0410\u0425\u0422\u0410 \u0426\u0415\u041d\u0422\u0420\u0410\" \u041e\u0426\u0415\u041d\u0418\u041b\u0418 \u0412 $100 \u041c\u041b\u041d |access-date=26 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128003246/http://restate.ru/material/152481.html |archive-date=28 January 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* October 2013 \u2013 construction of box-type foundation has been started. According to the plan this part of the work is to be finished in 2014.<ref>[http://advis.ru/php/view_news.php?id=763315EE-9CD4-6040-80D4-FA160CE9C441 \u0420\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u044b \u043d\u0443\u043b\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043f\u043b\u043e\u0449\u0430\u0434\u043a\u0435 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\".]</ref>\n\n* December 2013 \u2013 mounting of the concrete disks to the [[diaphragm wall]] has started. Disks are to provide the diaphragm wall with more resistance to outside ground pressure.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rcmm.ru/content/topics/428.html |title=\u041d\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0431 \u0443 \u0424\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0432\u0430. |access-date=10 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317210545/http://rcmm.ru/content/topics/428.html |archive-date=17 March 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* April 2014 \u2013 construction of foundation pit for the skyscraper is over.<ref>[http://karpovka.net/2014/04/02/137579/ \u0413\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u043a\u043e\u0442\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u043d\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0430 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\"]</ref>\n* June 2014 \u2013 piling is completed. 264 piles were mounted for the tower of Lakhta Center, 848 piles were mounted for the mixed-use building and entrance arch and 968 piles were mounted for the stylobate (undergroung parking). All in all 2080 piles were dug in.<ref>[http://proektvlahte.ru/en/article/?id=892 All 2080 Piles in Lakhta Center Foundation]</ref>\n* September 2014 \u2013 excavation of the foundation pit for the mixed-use building has been finished. Foundation concreting has started.\n* February and March 2015 \u2013 the pouring of the bottom slab of the skyscraper's box shaped foundation over. 19,624 cubic meters of concrete were cast in the foundation.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.fontanka.ru/2015/03/02/169/ Alexey Miller: First floors of the skyscraper in Lakhta will appear this year]</ref>\n* June 2015 \u2013 construction of the underground floors has finished.\n* September 2015 \u2013 pouring of the 2m thick upper box foundation slab has been completed, which means that all works below zero elevation are finished.\n* September 2015 \u2013 the construction of the first floors of the tower core is underway.<ref>[http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/article/?id=1087 Pouring of the Upper Slab of the Lakhta Center Tower Foundation]</ref>\n* January 2016 \u2013 construction of the succeeding ten floors of the tower; works on stylobate complex.\n* April 2016 \u2013 construction of the tower core at floors 22-26. Installation of the metal farm in the 18-22nd floors of the tower.\n* May 2016 \u2013 glazing of the facade of the Tower has started.\n* September 2016 \u2013 construction of the tower core at floors 46-50.<ref>[https://www.liebherr.com/en/deu/latest-news/news-press-releases/detail/liebherr-tower-cranes-in-action-erecting-the-highest-building-in-europe.html?news.type=press/ Liebherr tower cranes in action erecting the highest building in Europe]</ref>\n* December 2016 \u2013 installation of facade at floors 16-18; construction of the tower core at floors 57-61 \n* February 2017 \u2013 Lahkta Center's tower reaches height of 260 metres; floors 61-64 are under construction.\n* April 2017 -  height exceeds 300 meters, making Lakhta Center a [[supertall]] building (international classification), work is being done on the 67 floor.\n* May 2017 - the skyscraper reached the height 327,6 meters, working on the 78th floor.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2017/05/13/034/ Lakhta Center outgrew the tower]</ref>\n* August 2017 - Installation of the spire starts at 83 floors.\n* 5 October 2017 - Lakhta center became the tallest building in Europe when it reached a height of 374 meters.<ref>[http://lakhta.center/en/article/?id=1280 European altitude record broken]</ref><ref>[http://www.euronews.com/2017/10/06/russian-skyscraper-becomes-europe-s-tallest-building# Russian skyscraper \u2018becomes Europe\u2019s tallest building]</ref>\n* 29 January 2018 - the height of Lakhta center project reached a height of 462 meters, the assembly of structures of the spire is completed. The glazing of the tower continues at floor 70.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6Y-0SYU5sJU Lakhta Center reached the design height]</ref>\n* On 27 June 2018, the initial commissioning of the building was carried out. Technical documentation, building plan and technical passport were prepared.<ref>[https://www.archdaily.com/898132/europes-tallest-skyscraper-approaches-completion-in-st-petersburg Europe's Tallest Skyscraper Approaches Completion in St Petersburg]</ref>\n* On 16 October 2018, Lakhta Center MFC JSC received authorization for commissioning of the facility. The relevant document was officially published by the State Construction Supervision and Inspection Service of Saint Petersburg, Russia. There is about a year to go until the opening of Lakhta Center Multifunctional Complex, its dominant being the tallest skyscraper of Europe.<ref>[https://lakhta.center/en/article/?id=1321 Lakhta Center Officially Commissioned]</ref>\n\nNext to the already commissioned Lakhta Center, construction continues. To the four objects of the complex (tower, multi-purpose building, arch, stylobate) will be added one more. According to official documents, it takes place under the name \"Complex of buildings and structures\", or simply KZS.<ref>[https://www.fontanka.ru/2019/03/28/111/ \"Complex of buildings and structures\"]</ref>\n\nThe complex of buildings and structures is a single building consisting of two buildings connected by a courtyard. The authors of the project suggest that it will not only strengthen the office function of the Lakhta Center, but also complete the formation of the architectural ensemble, balancing the skyscraper in the horizontal.<ref>[https://www.the-village.ru/village/city/news-city/345989-kzs-lahta \"Complex of buildings and structures\". It will be built at the \"Lakhta center\" in 2021]</ref> The total area of the Lakhta center is 400 000 m\u00b2. With the addition of the KZS, the total area of the complex is 570 000 m\u00b2.<ref>[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/news.asp?id=924846&sec=1679 \u041a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u043a\u0440\u0443\u0433 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442 Renaissance Construction]</ref>\n\n== Multi-functional building ==\nMulti-functional building (MFZ) - an object divided into two buildings - North and South, which are United by a common Foundation, stylobate and roof. The building resembles a boomerang. It has a variable number of storeys with a height difference from 7 to 17 floors, with the peak height being a little more than 80 meters. The building is approximately 300 meters long.  Feature - negative angle of the end facades due to the removal of the console on 25 m. Facades - glass, with a total area of more than 60 thousand m2.<ref>[https://habr.com/ru/company/lakhtacenter/blog/371535/ Horizontal versus vertical. Or for? Why Lakhta Center \"recumbent\" dominant]</ref>\n\nConstructive scheme of the building - frame. More than 24 thousand tons of metal structures were used for the construction of this facility.\n\nThe main load-bearing elements are 4 reinforced concrete cores which perceive horizontal and vertical loadings, transferring them to the base executed in the form of the plate grillage leaning against piles. Between the Southern and Northern buildings of the MFZ along the entire height of the atrium, with a roof of translucent polymer membranes ETFE. In the space of the atrium, transitional bridges are spanned, which serve as observation points. Atrium is a pedestrian area from which you can get to any of the objects of the building.\n\nThe MFZ will house a number of public spaces - for example, a planetarium in the shape of a ball or a seven-storey hall-transformer, which can take different configurations: from the classical parquet to the amphitheater.\n\n== Design ==\n\n=== Facilities ===\nLakhta Center will contain offices, a [[co-working]] center, a sports center, a children's science center, and a conference center. Lakhta Center's project includes 1,500 square meters of indoor exhibition space. Part of the open area will be used to demonstrate objects of art, installations and sculptures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/ru/press/gallery/presentation/?id=445|title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044b {{!}} \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u2013 \u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0444\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u0432 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0435 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430|website=www.proektvlahte.ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref> There will be a free public observation deck at the top of the skyscraper at the height of 357m.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/about/objects/viewpoint/|title=Observation deck {{!}} \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u2013 \u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0444\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u0432 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0435 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430|website=www.proektvlahte.ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2014/08/19/122/|script-title=ru:\u0421\u043c\u043e\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0443\u044e \u043f\u043b\u043e\u0449\u0430\u0434\u043a\u0443 \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0434\u0443\u044e\u0442 \u0446\u0438\u0444\u0440\u043e\u0432\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0430\u043c\u0438|date=2014-08-19|accessdate=2018-07-30|language=ru}}</ref> Planetarium - a 19-meter sparkling ball on the surface of which 1223 curved triangular stainless steel sheet, polished to a Shine. The most accurate projection of the starry sky is formed by a star machine (Japanese projector - Ohira Tech Megastar-IIA ), and larger objects, artificial aircraft, visual effects and much more \u2013 digital, created by a projection system with a resolution of 8K Meridian, which uses 10 laser 4K projectors SONY GTZ280. Five projectors illuminate the lower tier of the dome, four \u2013 the top, and one forms an image at the Zenith. Thus, the total resolution in 48 483 533 pixels.<ref>[https://habr.com/ru/company/lakhtacenter/blog/447764/ \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e \u043a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0441! \u041a\u0430\u043a \u0443\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043d \u043f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430]</ref>\n\n=== Features ===\n\n* The main entrance of Lakhta Center is designed to be an [[arch]]. The height of the arch is almost 24m while its length is 98m.\n* There will be 34 elevators in the tower, but not all of them will travel to the top floor. The mixed-use building will contain 62 elevators. Besides these elevators there will be special firefighter lifts constructed to be used in case of emergency. The total capacity of all elevators is up to 1,280 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nvspb.ru/stories/neboskreby-menyayut-soznanie-sociuma-52309|title=\"\u041d\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0451\u0431\u044b \u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f\u044e\u0442 \u0441\u043e\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u043e\u0446\u0438\u0443\u043c\u0430\" {{!}} \u041d\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u044f|website=www.nvspb.ru|language=ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref>\n* Lakhta Center's foundation is going to be concreted continuously in round-the-clock mode. Constructors plan to pour 24,000 cubic metres in 48 hours. The volume of concrete to be poured under the mixed-use building near the tower is 48,000 cubic metres. This volume is large enough to be included in the [[Guinness Book of Records]].<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/exclusives.asp?id=447425 Construction director of Lakhta Center Elena Morozova: \"We will become record-holders due to the volume of concrete poured\"]</ref>\n* Around 400,000 cubic meters of concrete will be used for Lakhta Center's construction. During the first stage of foundation concreting 8,500 cubic meters of concrete will be used.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dp.ru/a/2014/12/08/Beton_dlja_Lahta_Centra/|title=\u0412 \u0441\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435 \u0434\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0431\u0440\u044f \u043d\u0430\u0447\u043d\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u0444\u0443\u043d\u0434\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\"|website=www.dp.ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref>\n* The area of glazing of the Tower totals 72,500 square meters as the area of the glazing for the complex in the whole makes up 130,000 square meters.<ref>[http://www.megapolis-online.ru/articles/intervyu/lahta-centr-462-metra-nad-urovnem-morya-1.html \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440. 462 \u043c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0434 \u0443\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0435\u043c \u043c\u043e\u0440\u044f]</ref>\n* Lakhta Center is designed to a high safety standard, which allows it to stand on one core even if all ten supportive columns collapse. The core structure is up to the highest fire rating. The building is designed to be able to withstand a four-hour fire without any structural damage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.popmech.ru/technologies/48791-kak-stroitsya-lakhta-tsentr-v-sankt-peterburge/#full|script-title=ru:\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0441\u044f \u00ab\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u00bb \u0432 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435|work=Popmech.ru|access-date=2018-07-30|language=ru-RU}}</ref>\n* On December 31, 2018 [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qlwYShApM9U Green Christmas lights] were lit on the skyscraper, thus turning the building into the highest Christmas tree in Europe<ref>[https://forpost-sz.ru/a/2018-12-31/lakhta-centr-prevratili-v-samuyu-vysokuyu-yolku-evropy The tallest Christmas tree in Europe]</ref>\n* On June 28, 2019, an automatic weather station was installed at the highest point of the spire (462 meters), which monitors temperature, humidity, wind direction and speed.<ref>[https://www.fontanka.ru/2019/06/28/053/ From Lakhta Center will now monitor the weather. On the spire of the St. Petersburg skyscraper appeared weather station]</ref>\n* 2019 - the Lakhta center complex became the leader in the number of nominations for the Award of Excellence and Urban Habitat.<ref>[https://tallinnovation.com/program/projects-featured/ Award of Excellence Winners]</ref> It was a finalist in five categories: Best high-rise building of 400 meters and higher; Construction award; Award in the field of construction engineering; award in the field of geotechnical engineering; award for facade engineering.\n\n=== Innovations ===\nIn order to provide more effective fire-fighting, a HI-FOG water mist suppression system will be used. When the temperature exceeds 57&nbsp;\u00b0C, sprinklers creating a water mist will start working automatically. Along with the sprinklers, there will be drenchers which could be switched on manually or by the means of remote control in order to create a water curtain in an emergency.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php#101 \u041c\u041e \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u041e\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e \u041e\u0431 \u0438\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u0432 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0435\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427193513/http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php#101 |date=27 April 2017 }}</ref> Lakhta Center is also set to be the first skyscraper in St. Petersburg where an ice formation control system will be used. Heating of the glass at high floors will prevent ice accumulation and help maintain good visibility. The spire of the Tower will be made from metal gauze to prevent a layer of ice forming in winter.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=6 \u041c\u041e \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u041e\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e. \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440: \u043b\u0435\u0434 \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0440\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043c] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427193302/http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=6 |date=27 April 2017 }}</ref> Level of consumption of material and energetic resources is going to be decreased due to conversion of kinetic energy of the Center workers and visitors' steps to electric energy.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.regnum.ru/news/realestate/1784199.html \"\u0417\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\" \u0432 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435: \u044d\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0438\u044f \u0448\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0432 \u043e\u0441\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0442 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\"]</ref>\nIn periods of birds' migration special illumination will be used to light the tower.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.gazeta.ru/realty/2015/05/06_a_6668381.shtml Lakhta Center Skyscraper Continues to Surprise with its Technologies]</ref>\n\n=== Environmental technologies ===\nWhile designing Lakhta Center several \"green\" and energy-saving technologies were planned for further application. They are\n\n* Double facade. Usage of double glazing will help to increase the level of thermal insulation, which allowed the designers to reduce costs for heating and conditioning.\n* Usage of the excess heat generated by working technical equipment for the heating of premises.\n* Usage of equipment with reduced noise level along with noise suppressors, sound-proof curtain walls and [[floating floor]]s.\n* Usage of economical infrared radiators.\n* Usage of contactless sensors or [[motion detectors]] for economizing electric energy and water.\n* Mounting of the systems supporting the optimal level of temperature and humidity inside the building.\n* Smart waste disposal system which improves hygiene and reduces CO2 emissions. Also wastes are sorted, which is one of the essential principles of green construction. Waste disposal is required by 20 times less frequent than in a conventional system.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.megapolis-online.com/articles/intervyu/lahta-centr-462-metra-nad-urovnem-morya-1.html Lakhta Center: 462 meters above the sea level] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170208073228/http://www.megapolis-online.com/articles/intervyu/lahta-centr-462-metra-nad-urovnem-morya-1.html |date=8 February 2017 }}</ref>\n* Constructing of the ice storages which will accumulate up to 1000 tons of ice at night for air conditioning during the daytime. It will help to reduce the differences in the usage of electricity during the night and day periods. It also allows reducing expenditures on electric power on the account of the differences in tariffs for day and night usage of electricity. As the cooling of the building is to be made using accumulative ice generators it will be possible to save on electricity expenditures up to 13 thousand rubles a day.\n* In support to the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] and FLAP's (Fatal Light Awareness Program) \"Bird - Friendly Building Program\", Lakhta Center's illumination will be designed so to make the building bird-safe especially in the periods of migration of birds (autumn, winter). The system of the illumination intensity and color change is under development at the moment.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=lakhta-tsentr-stremitsya-podruzhitsya-s-ptitsami Lakhta Center is eager to make friends with birds] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428052153/http://old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=lakhta-tsentr-stremitsya-podruzhitsya-s-ptitsami |date=28 April 2017 }}</ref>\n* Due to the peculiarities of the highly humid and windy climate in the North Western region of Russia the possibility of icing up of buildings is relatively high. In order to prevent complete icing up of the spire of the Lakhta Center's tower engineers changed glassing to the metal gauze.<ref>[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/news.asp?id=544242&sec=1671 \u0421\u043f\u0435\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0433\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044b \u043f\u043e\u0437\u0432\u043e\u043b\u044f\u0442 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0443\" \u044d\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0434\u043e 13 \u0442\u044b\u0441. \u0440\u0443\u0431. \u0432 \u0441\u0443\u0442\u043a\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u044d\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0440\u043e\u044d\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0438\u0438]</ref>\n* In order to provide Lakhta Center and adjoining areas with electricity without making any extra burden on existing infrastructure a new standalone power substation \"Nevskaya guba\" will be constructed.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://asninfo.ru/news/v-lahte-postroyat-podstanciyu-nevskaya-guba \"Nevskaya guba\" power substation will be built in Lakhta]</ref>\n\nAll in all, while constructing Lakhta Center approximately 100 [[innovation]]s are to be used. It lets increase the indexes of energy saving by 40% compared to the buildings where standard technologies are in use.\n\nIn experts' opinion, period of recoupment of using green and energy-saving technologies in Lakhta Center may be at about 20 years though Lakhta Center's Projection department's specialists think that this figure is a bit overestimated.\n\n===Transportation development===\nLakhta Center's construction raises a problem of transportation development because of the expected growth of the traffic flow in the region. Two traffic circles are to be built near Lakhta Center. These will become part of the \u041c32\u0410 highway in the future.<ref>[http://www.spbdnevnik.ru/news/2014-07-10/dva-razvorotnykh-koltsa-poyavyatsya-v-primorskom-rayone/]</ref>\nA light rail service from [[Finland Railway Station]] and a new tram line from Primorskaya underground station will be built to serve Lakhta Center. Plans are ongoing to build a new underground station with the working title of \"Lakhta\".<ref>[http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/about/transport/ Transport Infrastructure Development]</ref> Bicycle lanes near Lakhta Center with 90 parking places for bicycles are also planned.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2014/07/15/138/ \u0412 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u044f\u0437\u043a\u0438 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u044b \u041c-32 \u0438 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0448\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0443\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u0438 \u0432\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u043a\u0443]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/obshchestvennye-slushaniya-.php |title=\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0448\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f |access-date=18 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413143303/http://lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/obshchestvennye-slushaniya-.php |archive-date=13 April 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\nAs the [[Historic Centre of Saint Petersburg and Related Groups of Monuments|historical center of St. Petersburg]] has become a [[World Heritage Site]] since 1990; The [[World Heritage Committee]] opposed the construction of the 400-metre tower of [[Okhta Center]] as it would affect the cityscape of historic Saint Petersburg.<ref>[https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/612 UNESCO welcomes backing by President of Russian Federation for the preservation of St Petersburg]</ref> In December 2006 [[UNESCO]] World Heritage Centre Director Francesco Bandarin reminded Russia about its obligations to preserve it and expressed concern over the project.<ref>[http://www.vedomosti.ru/newspaper/article.shtml?2006/12/05/117081 UNESCO is worried] by Elena Ragozina, [[Vedomosti]] #229 (1756), 5 December 2006 (in Russian).</ref> In 2007, the [[World Monuments Fund]] placed the historic skyline of St. Petersburg on its 2008 Watch List of 100 Most Endangered Sites due to the potential construction of the building, and in 2009 reported that the tower \"would damage the image of Russia.\"<ref name=BBCUNESCO>{{Cite news |title=Russian tower plans cause alarm |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8272401.stm |publisher=BBC News |date=2009-09-23 |accessdate=2009-10-12}}</ref> During the 36 session of the World Heritage Committee of UNESCO held in Saint Petersburg in 2012 it was stated that a large area of Saint-Petersburg falls within preservation and buffer zones provided for UNESCO World Heritage Sites. That is why it is good for the city that the Okhta Center, which had been planned by Gazprom in front of Smolny Cathedral was moved to Lakhta.<ref>[https://whc.unesco.org/en/sessions/36COM 36th session of the Committee of the World Heritage Committee]</ref> Eleonora Mitrofanova, Permanent Representative of the Russian Federation to UNESCO noticed that the approved construction project for Lakhta Center is located far from the buffer zone and the historical center, so in theory Gazprom is not even obliged to ask UNESCO. However, the government authorities will definitely have consultations for the project with UNESCO. Now we are working to clarify the boundaries of the World Heritage zone and the boundaries of the buffer zone.<ref>[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/news.asp?id=326845&sec=1671 \u0412\u044b\u0441\u043e\u0442\u043a\u0430 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0442 \u043f\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0440\u0430\u043c\u0443 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430 \u0441\u043e \u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0424\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0432\u0430 \u2014 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434 \u0420\u0424 \u0432 \u042e\u041d\u0415\u0421\u041a\u041e]</ref>\n\nThe project being moved to Lakhta didn't stop the discussions. On 11 April 2012, ex-governor of St. Petersburg and now Federation Council chairwoman Valentina Matvienko said to journalists that the \"Lakhta center could become a new symbol of the city and attract the businessmen from all over the world to St. Petersburg.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo.msk.ru/programs/sorokina/876139-echo/ |title=\"In the light circle\", the interview with Ms.Matvienko at \"Echo Moskvy\" |publisher=Echo.msk.ru |date= |accessdate=2012-10-28}}</ref>\n\nDuring his visit to Russia in 2011 the Chairman of the [[Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat]] Professor Sang-Dae Kim was treated to a presentation of a project of Lakhta Center. Professor Kim commented on the \"modern shape\" of the proposed Lakhta Center, which according to him had \"nothing in common with ordinary boxes\".<ref>[http://www.ctbuh.org/Events/ToursVisits/ProfKimVisitstoSEAsiaRussia/ProfKimvisitRussia/tabid/2778/language/en-US/Default.aspx CTBUH Meeting: Russia]</ref> He also stated that something new ought to be created, which can be shown to new generations in 200\u2013300 years as for them what is created nowadays will be the same history as the architecture of the 18-19th centuries for us today. Professor also noticed that the project reminds him of an oriental concept [[Yin Yang]]: on the one hand, the historic part of the city with horizontal buildings and water, and on the other hand, a vertical which will add additional charm to the city. Lakhta Center combines an interesting form and modern technologies, so up to Mr. Kim, with the lapse of time the Center can become a new symbol of Saint Petersburg.<ref>[http://www.gazeta.ru/realty/2011/09/07_a_3759709.shtml Without skyscrapers Russia is the Kremlin and the Red Army]</ref>\n\nOn 16 May 2012, St. Petersburg governor Georgiy Poltavchenko emphasized in his annual report for House of Assembly the necessity of building a new \"city\" in St. Petersburg. According to Mr Poltavchenko, there are three appropriate districts for that: Lakhta center, Pulkovo and [[aggradation|aggradated]] territories near Waterfront.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/05/15/056/ |title=Poltavchenko: Petersburg needs a new business center and town-planning dictation |publisher=Fontanka.ru |date=2012-05-15 |accessdate=2012-10-28}}</ref>\n\n==Construction gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Site's view prior to construction.jpg|Site's view prior to construction, July 2012.\nFile:Aerial view of the construction site of Lakhta Center in Saint Petersburg, November 2014.jpg|Panoramic view of the construction site, November 2014.\nFile:Piling process.jpg|Piling process\nFile:Construction of the foundation under the Tower.jpg|Construction of the foundation under the Tower\nFile:Foundations of the Tower and mixed-use building are ready.jpg|Foundations of the tower and mixed-use building are ready\nFile:Lakhta Center.jpg|Lakhta Center. Nov, 2015\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0444\u0435\u0432\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c 2016).jpg|Lakhta Center. Feb, 2016\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0438\u044e\u043b\u044c 2016).jpg|Lakhta Center. Jul, 2016\nFile:Lakhta_Center_Oktober_2016.jpg|The state of the construction as of October, 2016\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043d\u043e\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c 2016).jpg|Lakhta Center. Nov, 2016\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0434\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0431\u0440\u044c 2016).jpg|Skyscraper at the end of 2016. Height is 245 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u043b\u044c 2017).jpg|Skyscraper in April 2017. Height is 310 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043c\u0430\u0439 2017).jpg|Lakhta Center in May 2017. Height is 323 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0441\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c 2017).jpg|Lakhta Center in September 2017. Height is 365 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440, \u044f\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044c 2018 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430.jpg|Lakhta Center in January 2018. Installation of the spire, height of about 450 meters\nFile:Lakhta Center orig.jpg|Skyscraper at the end of February 2018. Installation of the spire is complete, glazing of the tower and spire continues.\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043c\u0430\u044f\u043a).jpg|Lakhta Center in May 2018.\nFile:Das Lachta Zentr- \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 2H1A5980WI.jpg| June 2018\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043d\u043e\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c 2018).jpg|Lakhta Center in November 2018\nFile:2-\u044f \u043e\u0447\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u044c \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430.jpg|Construction of the 2nd stage (November 2018)\nFile:Lakhta Center at night in april 2019.jpg|April 2019\nFile:\u041d\u043e\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0444\u0430\u0441\u0430\u0434\u044b \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430.jpg|Skyscraper lighting\nFile:Lakhta Center, spire.jpg|The spire of the skyscraper (General view).\nFile:\u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445 \u0448\u043f\u0438\u043b\u044f \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430.jpg|The top of the spire. Floodlight projectors are integrated in it\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of tallest buildings in Russia]]\n*[[List of tallest buildings in Europe]]\n* [[List of twisted buildings]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/ Official site of Lakhta Center]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070401024640/http://www.ohta-center.ru/ Official Site of the Okhta Center project]\n* [http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/future/view/ Visual Analysis projecting the appearance of the tower at the Lakhta site, from various points in St. Petersburg]\n* [https://ru-ru.facebook.com/lakhtacenter.ru/ Official social media page]\n\n{{Supertall skyscrapers}}\n\n[[Category:Saint Petersburg culture]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Saint Petersburg]]\n[[Category:Architecture of Russia]]\n[[Category:Gazprom]]\n[[Category:Skyscrapers in Russia]]\n[[Category:Twisted buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures under construction in Russia]]\n", "name_user": "Galebazz", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInnovations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lakhta_Center"}
{"title_page": "Emmanuel Episcopal Church (Geneva)", "text_new": "<!-- Note: The following pages were redirects to [[Emmanuel_Episcopal_Church_(Geneva)]] before draftification:\n*[[Emmanuel Church, Geneva]]\n*[[Emmanuel Church Geneva]]\n-->\n\n{{Infobox church\n| name                   = Emmanuel Episcopal Church\n| other name             = formerly: The American Church\n| denomination           = [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America|Episcopal]]\n| architect              = Church: M. F. Gindroz,  Parish House: E. Fatio\n| completed date         = 1878 & 1930\n| website                = {{URL|www.emmanuelchurch.ch}}\n| image                  = Emmanuel_Church_Geneva_front_view.jpg\n| caption                = Front of the church\n| pushpin map            = Switzerland\n| pushpin label position = \n| pushpin map alt        = The location of Emmanuel Church on a map of Switzerland\n| relief                 = yes\n| pushpin mapsize        = \n| map caption            = The location of Emmanuel Church\n| coordinates            = {{coord|46|12|35.45|N|6|8|59.71|E|region:CH|display=inline,title}}\n| country                = [[Switzerland]]\n| founded date           = 1877\n| consecrated date       = 1878\n| bells                  = 1 (installed 1978)\n| diocese                = [[Convocation of Episcopal Churches in Europe]]\n| bishop                 = Mark D. W. Edington\n| rector                 = Michael F. Rusk\n| deacon                 = Richard Cole\n| organistdom            = Shauna Beesley\n}}\n\n'''Emmanuel Episcopal Church''', located in [[Geneva, Switzerland]], is an [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal]] parish of the [[Convocation of Episcopal Churches in Europe]], and a member of the [[Anglican Communion]]. The church has previously been known as \"The American Church\" (and informally as \"The American Chapel\")<ref name=Carpenter>{{cite book |last1=Carpenter |first1=G\u00e9rald |title=The American Church in Geneva\u202f: a century of service, 1873-1973 |date=1973 |publisher=Centennial Committe of Emmanuel Church}}</ref>, but this designation was abandoned in 1977 in the light of a decreasing American participation in the congregation.<ref name=Smiley />\n\n'''In response to the [[Coronavirus_disease_2019|Covid-19]] epidemic, the building is currently closed to the public.'''\n\n== Early history<ref name=Carpenter /> ==\n\nIn 1872 a multi-denominational group of Americans requested support from the Episcopal Church of the USA to found a church in Geneva.  This was denied and the group independently founded a \"Union\" church that year.  In 1873 the Episcopal Church did send Rev. William Chauncy Langdon DD to found a church in Geneva.  The first service was held in the Temple de la Fusterie on 28 July, 1873.  A period of friction between the two churches came to an end when they were merged in June 1875.\n\n== Building ==\n\nThe foundation stone of the building was laid on 27 July 1877 by former American President [[Ulysses S. Grant|Ulysses Grant]] on land donated by Henry I. Barbey, on what was the the Rue des Voirons. The first services took place in the church in 1878.<ref name=Carpenter /><ref name=Smiley>{{cite book |last1=Smiley |first1=Tex |title=Emmanuel Church - The fifth quarter century 1973-1998 |date=August 1998 |publisher=125th Celebration Committee of Emmanuel Church |location=Geneva}}</ref><ref name=Sauterel>{{cite web |last1=Sauterel |first1=Val\u00e9rie |title=American Emmanuel Episcopal Church |url=https://vitrosearch.ch/fr/buildings/2176435 |website=VitroSearch (in French) |date=2008}}</ref>  Constrained by its surroundings, the church building lies on a South-West to North-East axis.\n\nAn extension, the Parish House, was opened in November 1930, containing the Parish Halls, offices and the Library in English (formerly the \"American Library\").  In 1976 the Parish House suffered damage from subsidence caused by the excavation for a new hotel nearby.<ref name=Smiley />\n\nThe current organ, by [[Hans F\u00fcglister]], was dedicated on 23 June 1991.\n\n== Windows ==\nThe first of the windows was ordered from London and installed in May 1882.<ref name=Sauterel /><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kocher |first1=Magalie |title=Inventaire des vitraux des \u00e9glises anglicanes de l'arc l\u00e9manique |journal=M\u00e9moire de Licence, Facult\u00e9 des Lettres, Universit\u00e9 de Lausanne |date=2001}}</ref>  The windows are subject to a preservation order.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} The window above the altar (the \"East\" window) was originally illuminated by natural light, but the construction of the Parish House required it to be lit from behind with artificial light.  It is exceptional in that it depicts both [[Christ in Majesty|Christ in Glory]] and [[Jesus]] as a baby; a window in [[Genoa]] is the only other known in Europe.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nThe stained glass in the Parish Hall (''petite salle'') is by R. B\u00e9guin from 1993.\n\n[[File:Emmanuel_Altar_Window.jpg|thumb|right|The Altar or \"East\" Window]]\n\n\"North\" side windows:\n{|style=\"margin: 0 auto;\"\n| [[File:Emmanuel_Church_Window_9.jpg|thumb|upright|x300px]]\n| [[File:Emmanuel_Church_Window_10.jpg|thumb|upright|x300px]]\n| [[File:Emmanuel_Church_Window_1.jpg|thumb|upright|x300px]]\n| [[File:Emmanuel_Church_Window_2.jpg|thumb|upright|x300px]]\n| [[File:Emmanuel_Church_Window_3.jpg|thumb|upright|x300px]]\n|}\n\"South\" side windows:\n{|style=\"margin: 0 auto;\"\n| [[File:Emmanuel_Church_Window_4.jpg|thumb|upright|x300px]]\n| [[File:Emmanuel_Church_Window_5.jpg|thumb|upright|x300px]]\n| [[File:Emmanuel_Church_Window_6.jpg|thumb|upright|x300px]]\n| [[File:Emmanuel_Church_Window_7.jpg|thumb|upright|x300px]]\n| [[File:Emmanuel_Church_Window_8.jpg|thumb|upright|x300px]]\n|}\n\n==Community==\nThe community of Emmanuel reflects the diversity of the city of [[Geneva#Demographics|Geneva]] and the belief \"God loves you. No exceptions\".<ref name=\"What we believe\">{{cite web |title=What we believe |url=https://episcopalchurch.org/what-we-believe |publisher=The Episcopal Church|date=May 2017 }}</ref> The 2016 Parish Survey<ref name=\"Rector search\">{{cite web |title=Rector Search |url=https://docplayer.net/amp/29125206-Emmanuel-church-geneva.html|publisher= Emmanuel Church|date=2016}}</ref> indicated that 45% of parishioners come from the United States and 61% consider English to be their native tongue. However over 20 different languages are spoken, and 57% of parishioners described themselves as fluent in three or more. French is spoken by 87% of the community. The diversity of religious backgrounds includes Episcopalian 24%, [[Roman Catholic]] 20%, with a mixture of other [[Anglican]] and [[Protestant]] traditions contributing 45%.\n\nChurch services are conducted predominantly in English, with a few bilingual English/French services a year, often with the [[Christian Catholic Church of Switzerland|Old Catholic]] congregation of {{ill|\u00c9glise Saint-Germain de Gen\u00e8ve|fr|lt=St Germain}}. Sunday services take place at 8:00 ([[Holy Eucharist]]) and at 10:30 with music (Holy Eucharist or [[Daily Office (Anglican)|Morning Prayer]]).\n\n'''In response to the [[Coronavirus_disease_2019|Covid-19]] epidemic, the building is currently closed to the public.  Services will be \"live-streamed\", for details see the website.'''\n\nThe size of the congregation, being composed mainly of expatriates, has varied greatly over the years with changes in the political and economic climate. The church almost ceased to function during the periods of the two World Wars, but had a total Sunday congregation of over 300 in 1960.<ref name=Smiley />\n\nOnce a month, vulnerable women, with their children, are welcomed for lunch in the Parish Hall. Similarly, on a monthly basis, members of the congregation cook lunch for up to 180 of those in need at \"Jardin de Montbrillant\", the local [[Soup kitchen]].\n\n==Personalities==\n[[James T. Bates]], creator of the daily newspaper [[Tribune de Gen\u00e8ve]], was a founding member of the church and a member of the vestry for 38 years.<ref name=Carpenter /> A window on the \"North\" side is dedicated to him.\n\nHenry I. Barbey was a founding member of the church and a member of the vestry for 31 years.  He donated the land for the construction of the church building, and partially financed its construction and running during the early years.<ref name=Carpenter />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.emmanuelchurch.ch/ Emmanuel Church Website]\n\n[[Category:Episcopal (ECUSA) church buildings in Europe]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Geneva]]\n[[Category:Religious buildings and structures in Geneva]]\n[[Category:Churches in Geneva]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Note: The following pages were redirects to [[Emmanuel_Episcopal_Church_(Geneva)]] before draftification:\n*[[Emmanuel Church, Geneva]]\n*[[Emmanuel Church Geneva]]\n-->\n\n{{Infobox church\n| name                   = Emmanuel Episcopal Church\n| other name             = formerly: The American Church\n| denomination           = [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America|Episcopal]]\n| architect              = Church: M. F. Gindroz,  Parish House: E. Fatio\n| completed date         = 1878 & 1930\n| website                = {{URL|www.emmanuelchurch.ch}}\n| image                  = Emmanuel_Church_Geneva_front_view.jpg\n| caption                = Front of the church\n| pushpin map            = Switzerland\n| pushpin label position = \n| pushpin map alt        = The location of Emmanuel Church on a map of Switzerland\n| relief                 = yes\n| pushpin mapsize        = \n| map caption            = The location of Emmanuel Church\n| coordinates            = {{coord|46|12|35.45|N|6|8|59.71|E|region:CH|display=inline,title}}\n| country                = [[Switzerland]]\n| founded date           = 1877\n| consecrated date       = 1878\n| bells                  = 1 (installed 1978)\n| diocese                = [[Convocation of Episcopal Churches in Europe]]\n| bishop                 = Mark D. W. Edington\n| rector                 = Michael F. Rusk\n| deacon                 = Richard Cole\n| organistdom            = Shauna Beesley\n}}\n\n'''Emmanuel Episcopal Church''', located in [[Geneva, Switzerland]], is an [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal]] parish of the [[Convocation of Episcopal Churches in Europe]], and a member of the [[Anglican Communion]]. The church has previously been known as \"The American Church\" (and informally as \"The American Chapel\")<ref name=Carpenter>{{cite book |last1=Carpenter |first1=G\u00e9rald |title=The American Church in Geneva\u202f: a century of service, 1873-1973 |date=1973 |publisher=Centennial Committe of Emmanuel Church}}</ref>, but this designation was abandoned in 1977 in the light of a decreasing American participation in the congregation.<ref name=Smiley />\n\n'''In response to the [[Coronavirus_disease_2019|Covid-19]] epidemic, the building is currently closed to the public.'''\n\n== Early history<ref name=Carpenter /> ==\n\nIn 1872 a multi-denominational group of Americans requested support from the Episcopal Church of the USA to found a church in Geneva.  This was denied and the group independently founded a \"Union\" church that year.  In 1873 the Episcopal Church did send Rev. William Chauncy Langdon DD to found a church in Geneva.  The first service was held in the Temple de la Fusterie on 28 July, 1873.  A period of friction between the two churches came to an end when they were merged in June 1875.\n\n== Building ==\n\nThe foundation stone of the building was laid on 27 July 1877 by former American President [[Ulysses S. Grant|Ulysses Grant]] on land donated by Henry I. Barbey, on what was the the Rue des Voirons. The first services took place in the church in 1878.<ref name=Carpenter /><ref name=Smiley>{{cite book |last1=Smiley |first1=Tex |title=Emmanuel Church - The fifth quarter century 1973-1998 |date=August 1998 |publisher=125th Celebration Committee of Emmanuel Church |location=Geneva}}</ref><ref name=Sauterel>{{cite web |last1=Sauterel |first1=Val\u00e9rie |title=American Emmanuel Episcopal Church |url=https://vitrosearch.ch/fr/buildings/2176435 |website=VitroSearch (in French) |date=2008}}</ref>  Constrained by its surroundings, the church building lies on a South-West to North-East axis.\n\nAn extension, the Parish House, was opened in November 1930, containing the Parish Halls, offices and the Library in English (formerly the \"American Library\").  In 1976 the Parish House suffered damage from subsidence caused by the excavation for a new hotel nearby.<ref name=Smiley />\n\nThe current organ, by [[Hans F\u00fcglister]], was dedicated on 23 June 1991.\n\n== Windows ==\nThe first of the windows was ordered from London and installed in 1882.<ref name=Sauterel /><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kocher |first1=Magalie |title=Inventaire des vitraux des \u00e9glises anglicanes de l'arc l\u00e9manique |journal=M\u00e9moire de Licence, Facult\u00e9 des Lettres, Universit\u00e9 de Lausanne |date=2001}}</ref>  The windows are subject to a preservation order.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} The window above the altar (the \"East\" window) was originally illuminated by natural light, but the construction of the Parish House required it to be lit from behind with artificial light.  It is exceptional in that it depicts both [[Christ in Majesty|Christ in Glory]] and [[Jesus]] as a baby; a window in [[Genoa]] is the only other known in Europe.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nThe stained glass in the Parish Hall (''petite salle'') is by R. B\u00e9guin from 1993.\n\n[[File:Emmanuel_Altar_Window.jpg|thumb|right|The Altar or \"East\" Window]]\n\n\"North\" side windows:\n{|style=\"margin: 0 auto;\"\n| [[File:Emmanuel_Church_Window_9.jpg|thumb|upright|x300px]]\n| [[File:Emmanuel_Church_Window_10.jpg|thumb|upright|x300px]]\n| [[File:Emmanuel_Church_Window_1.jpg|thumb|upright|x300px]]\n| [[File:Emmanuel_Church_Window_2.jpg|thumb|upright|x300px]]\n| [[File:Emmanuel_Church_Window_3.jpg|thumb|upright|x300px]]\n|}\n\"South\" side windows:\n{|style=\"margin: 0 auto;\"\n| [[File:Emmanuel_Church_Window_4.jpg|thumb|upright|x300px]]\n| [[File:Emmanuel_Church_Window_5.jpg|thumb|upright|x300px]]\n| [[File:Emmanuel_Church_Window_6.jpg|thumb|upright|x300px]]\n| [[File:Emmanuel_Church_Window_7.jpg|thumb|upright|x300px]]\n| [[File:Emmanuel_Church_Window_8.jpg|thumb|upright|x300px]]\n|}\n\n==Community==\nThe community of Emmanuel reflects the diversity of the city of [[Geneva#Demographics|Geneva]] and the belief \"God loves you. No exceptions\".<ref name=\"What we believe\">{{cite web |title=What we believe |url=https://episcopalchurch.org/what-we-believe |publisher=The Episcopal Church|date=May 2017 }}</ref> The 2016 Parish Survey<ref name=\"Rector search\">{{cite web |title=Rector Search |url=https://docplayer.net/amp/29125206-Emmanuel-church-geneva.html|publisher= Emmanuel Church|date=2016}}</ref> indicated that 45% of parishioners come from the United States and 61% consider English to be their native tongue. However over 20 different languages are spoken, and 57% of parishioners described themselves as fluent in three or more. French is spoken by 87% of the community. The diversity of religious backgrounds includes Episcopalian 24%, [[Roman Catholic]] 20%, with a mixture of other [[Anglican]] and [[Protestant]] traditions contributing 45%.\n\nChurch services are conducted predominantly in English, with a few bilingual English/French services a year, often with the [[Christian Catholic Church of Switzerland|Old Catholic]] congregation of {{ill|\u00c9glise Saint-Germain de Gen\u00e8ve|fr|lt=St Germain}}. Sunday services take place at 8:00 ([[Holy Eucharist]]) and at 10:30 with music (Holy Eucharist or [[Daily Office (Anglican)|Morning Prayer]]).\n\n'''In response to the [[Coronavirus_disease_2019|Covid-19]] epidemic, the building is currently closed to the public.  Services will be \"live-streamed\", for details see the website.'''\n\nThe size of the congregation, being composed mainly of expatriates, has varied greatly over the years with changes in the political and economic climate. The church almost ceased to function during the periods of the two World Wars, but had a total Sunday congregation of over 300 in 1960.<ref name=Smiley />\n\nOnce a month, vulnerable women, with their children, are welcomed for lunch in the Parish Hall. Similarly, on a monthly basis, members of the congregation cook lunch for up to 180 of those in need at \"Jardin de Montbrillant\", the local [[Soup kitchen]].\n\n==Personalities==\n[[James T. Bates]], creator of the daily newspaper [[Tribune de Gen\u00e8ve]], was a founding member of the church and a member of the vestry for 38 years.<ref name=Carpenter /> A window on the \"North\" side is dedicated to him.\n\nHenry I. Barbey was a founding member of the church and a member of the vestry for 31 years.  He donated the land for the construction of the church building, and partially financed its construction and running during the early years.<ref name=Carpenter />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.emmanuelchurch.ch/ Emmanuel Church Website]\n\n[[Category:Episcopal (ECUSA) church buildings in Europe]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Geneva]]\n[[Category:Religious buildings and structures in Geneva]]\n[[Category:Churches in Geneva]]\n", "name_user": "DaPi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWindows", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emmanuel_Episcopal_Church_(Geneva)"}
{"title_page": "William Douglas of Whittingehame", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=February 2012}}\n'''William Douglas of Whittingehame''' (c. 1540 \u2013 17 December 1595) was a Senator of the [[College of Justice]] at [[Edinburgh]], and a Royal conspirator.\n\n[[Image:Whittinghame Arms.jpg|thumb|right|300px]]\n\n==Family==\nWilliam Douglas was the eldest son and heir of William Douglas of [[Whittingehame]] (died bef. 24 August 1557) and his spouse Elizabeth (d. after 24 August 1557), daughter of Sir Robert Lauder of [[The Bass]] (d.1517/18) by his spouse, Elizabeth Lawson.<ref>''[[Great Seal of Scotland]]'', no 1995, 1 November 1648.</ref>\n\nThe Douglases of Whittingehame near Haddington, [[East Lothian]], had held the estate from before the 1500s.<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', no. 3725 in 1512.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHe obtained, following the [[Scottish Reformation]], on 17 August 1560 a charter of the ecclesiastical lands at Whittingehame from [[Claud Hamilton, 1st Lord Paisley|Claud Hamilton]], then Dean of [[Dunbar]].  This grant included \"8 husbandlands (208 acres) and four 'terras' cottages in the 'villa' of Whittinghame\".  He joined the [[Lords of the Congregation]] and seems to have been frequently employed by the [[General Assembly of the Church of Scotland]] in their communications with [[Mary, Queen of Scots]] and the [[Privy Council of Scotland]].\n\nIt is said that the plot to murder Mary's husband, [[Lord Darnley]], was discussed at length in the grounds of [[Whittinghame Castle]] early in 1566. The [[Privy Council of Scotland|Privy Council]] cited William Douglas of Whittinghame, brother to Master [[Archibald Douglas, Parson of Douglas]], as one of the conspirators in the murder of [[David Riccio]], for which he was pardoned on 24 December 1566. In 1567 he joined the Association for the Preservation of [[James VI]].<ref>''The Registers of the Privy Council of Scotland'', March 1566, pp 436\u2013437, 507.</ref> \n\nWhittingehame prospered under [[Regent Morton]].<ref>George R. Hewitt, ''Scotland Under Morton'' (Edinburgh, 1982), p. 37.</ref> Prior to 20 October 1575 he was appointed an Ordinary Lord in the [[College of Justice]].  On 9 January 1579 he and his brother Archibald were excused attendance at court due to Archibald's illness, which was thought to be so serious that his brother should not leave him. \n\nAfter the fall of Regent Morton in March 1581 Whittingehame was threatened with torture by the boot, a device to crush the victim's leg, as were other servants of the [[Archibald Douglas, 8th Earl of Angus|Earl of Angus]] and Morton including George Auchinleck. The inquiry was intended to find Morton guilty of the murder of [[Henry Stuart, Lord Darnley|Lord Darnley]]. Whittingehame offered to implicate others, provided he gained a remmission for himself. The English ambassador [[Thomas Randolph (diplomat)|Thomas Randolph]] was deeply disappointed with Whittingehame's compliance with the new regime, and disavowal of the letters he had recently brought from England which painted [[Esm\u00e9 Stewart, 1st Duke of Lennox|Esm\u00e9 Stewart]] in a bad light. Whittingehame proclaimed the letters forgeries made his brother Archibald. The confessions of Whittingehame and his colleagues led to the execution of Morton.<ref>''Calendat State Papers Scotland: 1574-1581'', vol. 5 (Edinburgh, 1907), pp. 662, 667, 671, 673, 675-9: George R. Hewitt, ''Scotland Under Morton'' (Edinburgh, 1982), pp. 193-4.</ref>\n\nOn 26 August 1582 he was cited in the Privy Council as one of the [[Raid of Ruthven|'Ruthven Raiders']].\n\nHe resigned his position at the College of Justice prior to 1 August 1590, on which day his son and heir Archibald was presented to it by King James VI, although these positions were not hereditary.<ref>David Dalrymple of Hailes, ''An Historical Account of the Senators of the College of Justice of Scotland'' (Edinburgh, 1849), p. 160.</ref>\n\nMaterial given on behalf of his grandson, the Field Marshal [[Robert Douglas, Count of Skenninge]], to the Swedish genealogical authorities, mention that this William, laird of Whittinghame, was sometime (perhaps around 1590) during the reign of [[James VI]] of Scotland, a Scots envoy to king [[Christian IV of Denmark]] and Norway (whose sister James VI married) (ref: Elgenstierna).\n\n==Marriage==\nWilliam Douglas married in 1566 Elizabeth (d. after 6 August 1608 when she was described as his 'relict'), daughter of Sir [[Richard Maitland]] of Lethington by his spouse Mariotta, daughter of Sir Thomas Cranstoun of Corsbie.  They had six sons and two daughters. Of them:\n* Sir Archibald Douglas of Whittinghame, Senator of the [[College of Justice]], who married in 1597, Helen Lumsden, and died between 1630 \u2013 1642 with no issue. He settled Whittingehame upon his niece Isobel's husband, Sir Arthur Douglas, a grandson of [[William Douglas, 6th Earl of Morton]].\n* Patrick Douglas of [[Standingstone]], [[East Lothian]] (witnessed a Sasine to \"his brother german\" Archibald on 7 May 1596), whose son, Field Marshal [[Robert Douglas, Count of Skenninge]], ''friherre'' (baron) of Skalby, [[Sweden]], was a commander in later stages of [[Thirty Years War]]. Patrick was maternal grandfather to [[Sir Robert Lauder of Beilmouth]].\n* James Douglas, described in the ''Great Seal'' 1 November 1648, as \"secretary to James VI\".\n* [[Richard Douglas (letter writer)|Richard Douglas]] of [[Newgrange]], East Lothian, and Brockholes, Berwickshire (alive 7 May 1596, when he witnessed a Sasine to \"his brother german\", Archibald).\n* Sir William Douglas of [[Stoneypath]], near [[Garvald, East Lothian|Garvald]] (d. between 1628\u20131642), whose son-in-law Sir Arthur Douglas, Knt., was eventual heir of [[Whittingehame]].\n* Margaret Douglas married Robert Sinclair of [[Longformacus]].\n* John Douglas, Minister of Canonbie, 1606.<ref>''Fasti Ecclesiae Scoticanae'', vol 1.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*''The Spottiswoode Miscellany'', vol. 2 (Edinburgh, 1845), p. 329.\n*''HMC Manuscripts of Colonel Mordaunt Hay of Duns Castle, et al'' (Hereford, 1909), p.70, no.195, Sasine of heir dated 7 May 1596.\n*Percy W.L. Adams, ''The History of the Douglas family of Morton in Nithsdale & Fingland'' etc., by , (Bedford, 1921), Appendix C, number 258, p.805.\n* [[Gustaf Elgenstierna]], vol 2. sub Douglas-Stjernorp.\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2012}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Douglas, William, of Whittinghame}}\n[[Category:1540s births]]\n[[Category:1595 deaths]]\n[[Category:Senators of the College of Justice]]\n[[Category:Lords of the Congregation]]\n[[Category:People from East Lothian]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Scottish royal pardons]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=February 2012}}\n'''William Douglas of Whittingehame''' (c. 1540 \u2013 17 December 1595) was a Senator of the [[College of Justice]] at [[Edinburgh]], and a Royal conspirator.\n\n[[Image:Whittinghame Arms.jpg|thumb|right|300px]]\n\n==Family==\nWilliam Douglas was the eldest son and heir of William Douglas of [[Whittingehame]] (died bef. 24 August 1557) and his spouse Elizabeth (d. after 24 August 1557), daughter of Sir Robert Lauder of [[The Bass]] (d.1517/18) by his spouse, Elizabeth Lawson.<ref>''[[Great Seal of Scotland]]'', no 1995, 1 November 1648.</ref>\n\nThe Douglases of Whittingehame near Haddington, [[East Lothian]], had held the estate from before the 1500s.<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', no. 3725 in 1512.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHe obtained, following the [[Scottish Reformation]], on 17 August 1560 a charter of the ecclesiastical lands at Whittingehame from [[Claud Hamilton, 1st Lord Paisley|Claud Hamilton]], then Dean of [[Dunbar]].  This grant included \"8 husbandlands (208 acres) and four 'terras' cottages in the 'villa' of Whittinghame\".  He joined the [[Lords of the Congregation]] and seems to have been frequently employed by the [[General Assembly of the Church of Scotland]] in their communications with [[Mary, Queen of Scots]] and the [[Privy Council of Scotland]].\n\nIt is said that the plot to murder Mary's husband, [[Lord Darnley]], was discussed at length in the grounds of [[Whittinghame Castle]] early in 1566. The [[Privy Council of Scotland|Privy Council]] cited William Douglas of Whittinghame, brother to Master [[Archibald Douglas, Parson of Douglas]], as one of the conspirators in the murder of [[David Riccio]], for which he was pardoned on 24 December 1566. In 1567 he joined the Association for the Preservation of [[James VI]].<ref>''The Registers of the Privy Council of Scotland'', March 1566, pp 436\u2013437, 507.</ref> \n\nWhittingehame prospered under [[Regent Morton]].<ref>George R. Hewitt, ''Scotland Under Morton'' (Edinburgh, 1982), p. 37.</ref> Prior to 20 October 1575 he was appointed an Ordinary Lord in the [[College of Justice]].  On 9 January 1579 he and his brother Archibald were excused attendance at court due to Archibald's illness, which was thought to be so serious that his brother should not leave him. \n\nAfter the fall of Regent Morton in March 1581 Whittingehame was threatened with torture by the boot, a device to crush the victim's leg, as were other servants of the [[Archibald Douglas, 8th Earl of Angus|Earl of Angus]] and Morton including George Auchinleck. The inquiry was intended to find Morton guilty of the murder of [[Henry Stuart, Lord Darnley|Lord Darnley]]. Whittingehame offered to implicate others, provided he gained a remmission for himself. The English ambassador [[Thomas Randolph (diplomat)|Thomas Randolph]] was deeply disappointed with Whittingehame's compliance with the new regime, and disavowal of the letters he had recently brought from England which painted [[Esm\u00e9 Stewart, 1st Duke of Lennox|Esm\u00e9 Stewart]] in a bad light. Whittingehame proclaimed the letters forgeries made his brother Archibald. The confessions of Whittingehame and his colleagues led to the execution of Morton.<ref>''Calendat State Papers Scotland: 1574-1581'', vol. 5 (Edinburgh, 1907), pp. 662, 667, 671, 673, 675-9: George R. Hewitt, ''Scotland Under Morton'' (Edinburgh, 1982), pp. 193-4.</ref>\n\nOn 26 August 1582 he was cited in the Privy Council as one of the [[Raid of Ruthven|'Ruthven Raiders']].\n\nHe resigned his position at the College of Justice prior to 1 August 1590, on which day his son and heir Archibald was presented to it by King James VI, although these positions were not hereditary.<ref>David Dalrymple of Hailes, ''An Historical Account of the Senators of the College of Justice of Scotland'' (Edinburgh, 1849), p. 160.</ref>\n\nMaterial given on behalf of his grandson, the Field Marshal [[Robert Douglas, Count of Skenninge]], to the Swedish genealogical authorities, mention that this William, laird of Whittinghame, was sometime (perhaps around 1590) during the reign of [[James VI]] of Scotland, a Scots envoy to king [[Christian IV of Denmark]] and Norway (whose sister James VI married) (ref: Elgenstierna).\n\n==Marriage==\nWilliam Douglas married in 1566 Elizabeth (d. after 6 August 1608 when she was described as his 'relict'), daughter of Sir [[Richard Maitland]] of Lethington by his spouse Mariotta, daughter of Sir Thomas Cranstoun of Corsbie.  They had six sons and two daughters. Of them:\n* Sir Archibald Douglas of Whittinghame, Senator of the [[College of Justice]], who married in 1597, Helen Lumsden, and died between 1630 \u2013 1642 with no issue. He settled Whittingehame upon his niece Isobel's husband, Sir Arthur Douglas, a grandson of [[William Douglas, 6th Earl of Morton]].\n* Patrick Douglas of [[Standingstone]], [[East Lothian]] (witnessed a Sasine to \"his brother german\" Archibald on 7 May 1596), whose son, Field Marshal [[Robert Douglas, Count of Skenninge]], ''friherre'' (baron) of Skalby, [[Sweden]], was a commander in later stages of [[Thirty Years War]]. Patrick was maternal grandfather to [[Sir Robert Lauder of Beilmouth]].\n* James Douglas, described in the ''Great Seal'' 1 November 1648, as \"secretary to James VI\".\n* Richard Douglas of [[Newgrange]], East Lothian, and Brockholes, Berwickshire (alive 7 May 1596, when he witnessed a Sasine to \"his brother german\", Archibald).\n* Sir William Douglas of [[Stoneypath]], near [[Garvald, East Lothian|Garvald]] (d. between 1628\u20131642), whose son-in-law Sir Arthur Douglas, Knt., was eventual heir of [[Whittingehame]].\n* Margaret Douglas married Robert Sinclair of [[Longformacus]].\n* John Douglas, Minister of Canonbie, 1606.<ref>''Fasti Ecclesiae Scoticanae'', vol 1.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*''The Spottiswoode Miscellany'', vol. 2 (Edinburgh, 1845), p. 329.\n*''HMC Manuscripts of Colonel Mordaunt Hay of Duns Castle, et al'' (Hereford, 1909), p.70, no.195, Sasine of heir dated 7 May 1596.\n*Percy W.L. Adams, ''The History of the Douglas family of Morton in Nithsdale & Fingland'' etc., by , (Bedford, 1921), Appendix C, number 258, p.805.\n* [[Gustaf Elgenstierna]], vol 2. sub Douglas-Stjernorp.\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2012}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Douglas, William, of Whittinghame}}\n[[Category:1540s births]]\n[[Category:1595 deaths]]\n[[Category:Senators of the College of Justice]]\n[[Category:Lords of the Congregation]]\n[[Category:People from East Lothian]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Scottish royal pardons]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMarriage:link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Douglas_of_Whittingehame"}
{"title_page": "Khwaja Ghulam Farid", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=January 2019}}\n{{short description|19th-century Sufi Saraiki poet and writer}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = Khawaja Ghulam Farid Koreja\n| native_name = \u062e\u0648\u0627\u062c\u06c1 \u063a\u064f\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0641\u0631\u06cc\u062f \u06a9\u064f\u0648\u0631\u06cc\u062c\u06c1\n| image = Khawaja Ghulam Farid tomb at Kot Mithan.jpg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| alt = \n| caption = Darbaar-e-Hazrat Khawaja Ghulam Farid Koreja\n| birth_date = {{birth year|1845}}<ref name=paknetmag/>\n| birth_place = [[Chachran]], [[Bahawalpur State]], [[British India]] (now [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], Pakistan)\n| death_date = {{death-date and age|24 July 1901|1845}}<ref name=paknetmag/>\n| death_place = [[Chachran]], [[Bahawalpur State]], [[British India]] (present-day [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], Pakistan)\n| resting_place = [[Mithankot]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], Pakistan\n| notablework = ''Deewan-e-Farid''\n\"Manaqabe Mehboobia\" (Persian prose)\n\"Fawaid Faridia\" (Persian prose)\n}}\n{{Islam}}\n'''Khawaja Ghulam Farid Koreja ''' ({{lang-pa|{{Nastaliq|\u062e\u0648\u0627\u062c\u06c1 \u063a\u064f\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0641\u0631\u06cc\u062f \u06a9\u064f\u0648\u0631\u06cc\u062c\u06c1}}}}) or '''Khawaja Farid''' (1845\u20131901) was a 19th-century [[Saraiki people|Saraiki]] [[Sufi]] [[poet]] of the [[Indian subcontinent]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cI1_AgAAQBAJ|title=Muslim Saints of South Asia: The Eleventh to Fifteenth Centuries (Islamic calendar)|first=Anna|last=Suvorova|date=22 July 2004|publisher=Routledge|via=Google Books}}</ref> He was a scholar and writer who knew several different languages. He belonged to the [[Chishti|Chishti\u2013Nizami]] [[Sufi order]]. He was known for his work which helped popularize the Saraiki language.\n\n[[Khawaja Fareed University of Engineering and Information Technology]] was named after him.\n\n==Early life==\nHis mother died when he was four years old and he was orphaned around the age of twelve when his father, Khawaja Khuda Bakhsh, died. He was then brought up by his elder brother, Khawaja Fakhr-ud-Din aka Khawaja Fakhr Jehan Sain, and grew up to become a scholar and writer. He mastered [[Saraiki language|Saraiki]], [[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[Persian language|Persian]],  [[Urdu]], [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]], and [[Braj Bhasha]], and also wrote [[kafi]] poems in the [[Saraiki language|Saraiki]], [[Urdu]], [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]], [[Persian language|Persian]], and [[Braj Bhasha]] languages.\n\nNawab [[Sadeq Mohammad Khan V]] of [[Bahawalpur]] took Khawaja Ghulam Farid Koreja to his palace at [[Ahmad pur sharkia|Ahmadpur Sharqia]] for his religious education by a scholar, when he was 8 years old. His elder brother Khawaja Fakhr-ud-Din Koreja who had brought him up after his parents' deaths, also died when Khawaja Ghulam Farid Koreja was 28 years old. Khawaja Ghulam Farid then left the [[Cholistan Desert]] (also known as ''Rohi'') and lived there for 18 years.\n\nKhawaja Ghulam Farid Koreja performed [[Hajj]], [[Islamic]] [[pilgrimage]] to [[Mecca]], in 1876.\n\n==Works==\nHis most significant works include:\n* ''Deewan-e-Farid'' (poem collection in [[Saraiki language|Saraiki]], 1882; in Urdu, 1884); Khwaja Farid composed as many as 272 poem[[kafi|s<nowiki/>]] of high literary merit.<ref>[https://www.dawn.com/news/1063376 A Khwaja Ghulam Farid anniversary] Dawn (newspaper), Published 20 July 2002, Retrieved 15 June 2018</ref>\n* ''Manaqabe Mehboobia'' (in Persian prose)\n* ''Fawaid Faridia'' (in Persian prose)\n\nIn his poetry, he frequently uses the symbolism of a desert. Talking about how beautiful the desert is and how it attracted him to stay there for 18 years and how he believed that made him feel close to [[Muhammad]]. Sometimes he touched the topic of political affairs, opposing the British rule in [[Bahawalpur]] state writing a letter to the [[Nawab of Bahawalpur]] and also mentioning it in some of his poetry.\n\n== Awards and Recognition ==\n*The 20th century saw the development of an entire branch of literary studies on the life and work of Khwaja Ghulam Farid Koreja, called ''faridiyat''.\n*Today, many religious and educational institutions in Pakistan and India are named after him (e.g., [[Government Khawaja Farid College]] in [[Rahimyar Khan]], Pakistan) as are streets and town living quarters. \n*A literary award named after him, ''Khwaja Ghulam Farid Award'' is awarded yearly by the [[Pakistan Academy of Letters]] in literature, its recipients including [[Ismail Ahmedani]] (in 2013) and Irshad Taunsvi (in 2007) among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/E-Paper/Lahore/2013-12-19/page-14/detail-10 |title=Pakistan Academy of Letters (PAL) confers awards on literary figures|author=Amir Jalil Bobra|date=19 December 2013|publisher=The Nation (newspaper)|accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref><ref>[http://apnaorg.com/announcement/pal/ PAL announces National Literary Awards] Academy of the Punjab in North America website, Published 10 August 2007, Retrieved 15 June 2018</ref>\n* In 2001, on Khwaja Ghulam Farid's 100th death anniversary (''[[urs]]''), [[Pakistan Post]] issued a memorial stamp to honor him in its 'Poets of Pakistan' series<ref name=paknetmag>[http://paknetmag.blogspot.com/search/label/Stamps%20of%20Pakistan%20Year%27s%202001 Profile of Khwaja Ghulam Farid on Paknetmag website] Retrieved 15 June 2018</ref>\n*The public school built by Nawab [[Sadeq Mohammad Khan V]] in Bahawalpur has a house named after Khwaja Ghulam Farid, called Farid House\n*Also one of the gates surrounding the inner city of Bahawalpur was named ''\u201cBab-e-Farid\u201d'' also known as ''\u201cFarid Gate\u201d'' after Khawaja Ghulam Farid\n*The [[Khawaja Fareed University of Engineering and Information Technology]] (KFUEIT)\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Fariduddin Ganjshakar]]\n*[[Punjabi literature]]\n* [[Muhammad Muslehuddin Siddiqui|Qari Muhammad Muslehuddin Siddiqui]]\n* [[Pathanay Khan]]\n* [[Christopher Shackle]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.apnaorg.com/poetry/kfarid/ The complete works of Khwaja Farid in Punjabi on Academy of the Punjab in North America website]\n\n{{Sufism}}\n{{South Asian Muslim Saints}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khwaja Ghulam Farid Korejo}}\n[[Category:1845 births|Farid, Khwaja]]\n[[Category:1901 deaths|Farid, Khwaja]]\n[[Category:Sufi mystics]]\n[[Category:Sufi poets]]\n[[Category:People of British India]]\n[[Category:Punjabi Sufi saints]]\n[[Category:Punjabi poets]]\n[[Category:19th-century poets]]\n[[Category:People from Rahim Yar Khan District]]\n[[Category:Saraiki-language poets]]\n[[Category:Saraiki-language writers]]\n[[Category:Chishti Order]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=January 2019}}\n{{short description|19th-century Sufi Saraiki poet and writer}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = Khawaja Ghulam Farid Koreja\n| native_name = \u062e\u0648\u0627\u062c\u06c1 \u063a\u064f\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0641\u0631\u06cc\u062f \u06a9\u064f\u0648\u0631\u06cc\u062c\u06c1\n| image = Khawaja Ghulam Farid tomb at Kot Mithan.jpg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| alt = \n| caption = Darbaar-e-Hazrat Khawaja Ghulam Farid Koreja\n| birth_date = {{birth year|1845}}<ref name=paknetmag/>\n| birth_place = [[Chachran]], [[Bahawalpur State]], [[British India]] (now [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], Pakistan)\n| death_date = {{death-date and age|24 July 1901|1845}}<ref name=paknetmag/>\n| death_place = [[Chachran]], [[Bahawalpur State]], [[British India]] (present-day [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], Pakistan)\n| resting_place = [[Mithankot]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], Pakistan\n| notablework = ''Deewan-e-Farid''\n\"Manaqabe Mehboobia\" (Persian prose)\n\"Fawaid Faridia\" (Persian prose)\n}}\n{{Islam}}\n'''Khawaja Ghulam Farid Koreja ''' ({{lang-pa|{{Nastaliq|\u062e\u0648\u0627\u062c\u06c1 \u063a\u064f\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0641\u0631\u06cc\u062f \u06a9\u064f\u0648\u0631\u06cc\u062c\u06c1}}}}) or '''Khawaja Farid''' (1845\u20131901) was a 19th-century [[Saraiki people|Saraiki]] [[Sufi]] [[poet]] of the [[Indian subcontinent]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cI1_AgAAQBAJ|title=Muslim Saints of South Asia: The Eleventh to Fifteenth Centuries (Islamic calendar)|first=Anna|last=Suvorova|date=22 July 2004|publisher=Routledge|via=Google Books}}</ref> He was a scholar and writer who knew several different languages. He belonged to the [[Chishti|Chishti\u2013Nizami]] [[Sufi order]]. He was known for his work which helped popularize the Saraiki language.\n\n[[Khawaja Fareed University of Engineering and Information Technology]] was named after him.\n\n==Early life==\nHis mother died when he was four years old and he was orphaned around the age of twelve when his father, Khawaja Khuda Bakhsh, died. He was then brought up by his elder brother, Khawaja Fakhr-ud-Din aka Khawaja Fakhr Jehan Sain, and grew up to become a scholar and writer. He mastered [[Saraiki language|Saraiki]], [[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[Persian language|Persian]],  [[Urdu]], [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]], and [[Braj Bhasha]], and also wrote [[kafi]] poems in the [[Saraiki language|Saraiki]], [[Urdu]], [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]], [[Persian language|Persian]], and [[Braj Bhasha]] languages.\n\nNawab [[Sadeq Mohammad Khan V]] of [[Bahawalpur]] took Khawaja Ghulam Farid Koreja to his palace at [[Ahmad pur sharkia|Ahmadpur Sharqia]] for his religious education by a scholar, when he was 8 years old. His elder brother Khawaja Fakhr-ud-Din Koreja who had brought him up after his parents' deaths, also died when Khawaja Ghulam Farid Koreja was 28 years old. Khawaja Ghulam Farid then left the [[Cholistan Desert]] (also known as ''Rohi'') and lived there for 18 years.\n\nKhawaja Ghulam Farid Koreja performed [[Hajj]], [[Islamic]] [[pilgrimage]] to [[Mecca]], in 1876.\n\n==Works==\nHis most significant works include:\n* ''Deewan-e-Farid'' (poem collection in [[Saraiki]], 1882; in Urdu, 1884); Khwaja Farid composed as many as 272 poem[[kafi|s<nowiki/>]] of high literary merit.<ref>[https://www.dawn.com/news/1063376 A Khwaja Ghulam Farid anniversary] Dawn (newspaper), Published 20 July 2002, Retrieved 15 June 2018</ref>\n* ''Manaqabe Mehboobia'' (in Persian prose)\n* ''Fawaid Faridia'' (in Persian prose)\n\nIn his poetry, he frequently uses the symbolism of a desert. Talking about how beautiful the desert is and how it attracted him to stay there for 18 years and how he believed that made him feel close to [[Muhammad]]. Sometimes he touched the topic of political affairs, opposing the British rule in [[Bahawalpur]] state writing a letter to the [[Nawab of Bahawalpur]] and also mentioning it in some of his poetry.\n\n== Awards and Recognition ==\n*The 20th century saw the development of an entire branch of literary studies on the life and work of Khwaja Ghulam Farid Koreja, called ''faridiyat''.\n*Today, many religious and educational institutions in Pakistan and India are named after him (e.g., [[Government Khawaja Farid College]] in [[Rahimyar Khan]], Pakistan) as are streets and town living quarters. \n*A literary award named after him, ''Khwaja Ghulam Farid Award'' is awarded yearly by the [[Pakistan Academy of Letters]] in literature, its recipients including [[Ismail Ahmedani]] (in 2013) and Irshad Taunsvi (in 2007) among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/E-Paper/Lahore/2013-12-19/page-14/detail-10 |title=Pakistan Academy of Letters (PAL) confers awards on literary figures|author=Amir Jalil Bobra|date=19 December 2013|publisher=The Nation (newspaper)|accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref><ref>[http://apnaorg.com/announcement/pal/ PAL announces National Literary Awards] Academy of the Punjab in North America website, Published 10 August 2007, Retrieved 15 June 2018</ref>\n* In 2001, on Khwaja Ghulam Farid's 100th death anniversary (''[[urs]]''), [[Pakistan Post]] issued a memorial stamp to honor him in its 'Poets of Pakistan' series<ref name=paknetmag>[http://paknetmag.blogspot.com/search/label/Stamps%20of%20Pakistan%20Year%27s%202001 Profile of Khwaja Ghulam Farid on Paknetmag website] Retrieved 15 June 2018</ref>\n*The public school built by Nawab [[Sadeq Mohammad Khan V]] in Bahawalpur has a house named after Khwaja Ghulam Farid, called Farid House\n*Also one of the gates surrounding the inner city of Bahawalpur was named ''\u201cBab-e-Farid\u201d'' also known as ''\u201cFarid Gate\u201d'' after Khawaja Ghulam Farid\n*The [[Khawaja Fareed University of Engineering and Information Technology]] (KFUEIT)\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Fariduddin Ganjshakar]]\n*[[Punjabi literature]]\n* [[Muhammad Muslehuddin Siddiqui|Qari Muhammad Muslehuddin Siddiqui]]\n* [[Pathanay Khan]]\n* [[Christopher Shackle]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.apnaorg.com/poetry/kfarid/ The complete works of Khwaja Farid in Punjabi on Academy of the Punjab in North America website]\n\n{{Sufism}}\n{{South Asian Muslim Saints}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khwaja Ghulam Farid Korejo}}\n[[Category:1845 births|Farid, Khwaja]]\n[[Category:1901 deaths|Farid, Khwaja]]\n[[Category:Sufi mystics]]\n[[Category:Sufi poets]]\n[[Category:People of British India]]\n[[Category:Punjabi Sufi saints]]\n[[Category:Punjabi poets]]\n[[Category:19th-century poets]]\n[[Category:People from Rahim Yar Khan District]]\n[[Category:Saraiki-language poets]]\n[[Category:Saraiki-language writers]]\n[[Category:Chishti Order]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSaraiki(link changed toSaraiki language) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Khwaja_Ghulam_Farid"}
{"title_page": "Cole Taylor", "text_new": "'''Cole Taylor''' was a [[pornographic actor]] who primarily worked in gay adult film in the 1980s. He debuted in 1984, delivered a notable performance in a [[bisexual]] film, and starred in what may be gay adult film's first [[safe sex]] film in 1985. He died in 1989.\n\nHe made his debut in the [[Nova Studios]] production ''Heroes'' (1984).<ref name=\"Hardesty12\">Hardesty, p. 12.</ref> His acting debut was inauspicious. One reviewer for ''[[Manshots]]'' magazine noted, \"...Taylor was certainly cute, but he lacked the look or sound of mature authority needed to play the role of a teacher convincingly. That was however, the role assigned him by [the director].\"<ref name=\"Hardesty12\" /> \"...Taylor's line readings sounded so frothily coy and cheerful, you'd have thought he'd studied with Billie Burke.  Miscasting, then had sabotaged a key part of the old Nova formula: That nothing in a man's looks, environment, or ''voice'' should seem stereotypically gay.\"<ref>Hardesty, p. 13. Emphasis in original.</ref>\n\nDespite this performance, Taylor continued to perform in adult film.  He turned in only two more notable performances, in ''Full Grown, Full Blown,''<ref>Adam Film World, 1991, p. 151.</ref> and the [[bisexual]] production ''Cross Over''.<ref name=\"Adam147\">Adam Film World, 1991, p. 147.</ref> Although his performance may not have been notable, another of his films was. ''Lifeguard'', an original performance produced in 1985 by HIS Video, may be the first [[safe sex]] gay adult film ever made.<ref>Burger, p. 27; Adam Film World, 1992, p. 158.</ref> In between scenes, Robert Bolan, president of the [[San Francisco AIDS Foundation]], discussed safe sex practices. Gay adult film historian Jeffrey Escoffier notes that the film showcased some of the most popular performers of the day, which included Taylor.<ref>Escoffier, p. 211-212.</ref> By the end of his career, Cole Taylor made about 25 pornographic films.<ref>The number of films Taylor made is unclear, because sources vary. According to Atkol Video, Taylor made 21 films. See: Atkol Video, p. 88. Bruce Wayne's directory of adult film lists 34 films. See: Wayne, p. 218. Atkol lists two films (''Bi-Ballers'' and ''Studio X'') which Wayne does not. A cast listing cannot be independently confirmed for ''Bi-Ballers'' by Adam Film World or [[Internet Adult Film Database]] (IAFD). However, although Adam Film World has no listing for ''Studio X'', IAFD confirms the existence of the film and that Taylor is in the cast. See: [http://www.iafd.com/person.rme/perfid=ColeTaylor/gender=m/Cole-Taylor.htm Cole Taylor. Internet Adult Film Database. No date], accessed 2013-04-21. Ten films listed by Wayne (''Best of Surge Vol. 2'', ''Climactic Scenes #101'', ''Fanta-size'', ''Guys Who Eat Cum'', ''Hot Shots Vol. 7: Daddies'', ''In Too Deep'', ''Lovers & Friends'', ''Magnum Griffin Vol. 6'', ''Muscle Studs'', and ''Tight Friendship'') are compilation films (existing scenes recut and repackaged) and not original productions. Of the remaining non-compilation films which Wayne lists, six films (''All Hands on Dick'', ''Hard Fucking Buddies'', ''Lifeguard'', ''Making It Huge'', ''One Size Fits All'', and ''Sighs'') are not listed by Atkol. Adam Film World confirms that Cole Taylor is in the cast of ''One Size Fits All'' and ''Sighs''. See: Adam Film World, 1992, p. 171, 175. The IAFD confirms Taylor is a cast member in ''All Hands on Dick'' and ''Making It Huge''. See: [http://www.iafd.com/person.rme/perfid=ColeTaylor/gender=m/Cole-Taylor.htm Cole Taylor. Internet Adult Film Database. No date], accessed 2013-04-21.  Both IAFD and Adam Film World confirm that Cole Taylor is in ''Lifeguard''. See: Adam Film World, p. 158; [http://www.iafd.com/person.rme/perfid=ColeTaylor/gender=m/Cole-Taylor.htm Cole Taylor. Internet Adult Film Database. No date], accessed 2013-04-21. No other database lists ''Hard Fucking Buddies'' and the existence of the film cannot be independently verified. Finally, neither Atkol nor Wayne list ''Cross Over'' as a Cole Taylor film. However, Adam Film World and IAFD confirm he is part of the cast of this bisexual film. See: Adam Film World, 1991, p. 147; [http://www.iafd.com/person.rme/perfid=ColeTaylor/gender=m/Cole-Taylor.htm Cole Taylor. Internet Adult Film Database. No date], accessed 2013-04-21. This leaves 25 films for Cole Taylor's original production filmography.</ref>\n\nAccording to adult film historian Rex Hardesty, Taylor died in 1989. Hardesty did not disclose the cause of death.<ref name=\"Hardesty12\" /> According to the industry publication ''Adam Film World'', Taylor was bisexual.<ref name=\"Adam147\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Adam Film World. ''1991 Directory of Gay Adult Videos.'' Los Angeles, Calif.: 1990.\n*Adam Film World. ''1992 Directory of Gay Adult Videos.'' Los Angeles, Calif.: 1991.\n*Atkol Video. ''Atkol Comprehensive Guide to Adult Male Videos.''  Plainfield, N.J.: Atkol, 1990.\n*Burger, John R. ''One-Handed Histories: The Eroto-Politics of Gay Male Video Pornography.'' New York: Haworth Press, 1995.\n*Escoffier, Jeffrey. ''Bigger Than Life: The History of Gay Porn Cinema From Beefcake to Hardcore.'' Philadelphia, Pa.: Running Press, 2009. \n*Hardesty, Rex. \"Nova Studios, Part Two: The Final Years.\" ''Manshots.'' August 1997.\n*Wayne, Bruce. ''Gay Porn Star Directory.'' Laguna Hills, Calif.: Companion Press, 2000.\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taylor, Cole}}\n[[Category:1989 deaths]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:American male pornographic film actors]]\n", "text_old": "'''Cole Taylor''' was a [[pornographic actor]] who primarily worked in gay adult film in the 1980s. He debuted in 1984, delivered a notable performance in a [[bisexual]] film, and starred in what may be gay adult film's first [[safe sex]] film in 1985. He died in 1989.\n\nHe made his debut in the [[Nova Studios]] production ''Heroes''