{"title_page": "Peter Cory", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian judge}}\n{{Infobox Judge\n| image =   |\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| office        = [[Puisne Justice]] of the [[Supreme Court of Canada]]\n| termstart     = February 1, 1989\n| termend       = June 1, 1999\n| nominator     = [[Brian Mulroney]]\n| appointer     = \n| predecessor   = [[Gerald Le Dain]]\n| successor     = [[Louise Arbour]]\n| office2       = \n| termstart2    = \n| termend2      = \n| nominator2    = \n| appointer2    = \n| predecessor2  = \n| successor2    = \n|birth_name     = Peter deCarteret Cory\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1925|10|25|mf=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Windsor, Ontario]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|2020|4|7|1925|10|25}}\n| death_place   = Mississauga\n| residence     = [[Mississauga, Ontario]]\n| spouse        = Edith Nash (deceased);  Mary Dayton \n}}\n'''Peter deCarteret Cory''', {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|CC|QC}} (October 25, 1925 \u2013 April 7, 2020) was a [[puisne judge]] of the [[Supreme Court of Canada]], from 1989 to 1999.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in [[Windsor, Ontario]], the son of Andrew and Mildred (Beresford Howe) Cory, he was educated at the [[University of Western Ontario]] (Assumption) receiving his [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in 1947 and at [[Osgoode Hall Law School]] receiving his law degree in 1950. He was called to the [[Ontario Bar]] in 1950.\n\n==Career==\nAs a pilot in the [[Royal Canadian Air Force]], he served overseas with 6th Bomber Group during [[World War II]], flying many combat missions. He was appointed to the [[Queen's Counsel]] in 1963. He practised law with Holden, Murdoch and was elected a Bencher of the [[Law Society of Upper Canada]] in 1971.\n\nCory was appointed to the [[Supreme Court of Ontario]] in 1974, the [[Court of Appeal for Ontario]] in 1981 and the Supreme Court of Canada on February 1, 1989. He retired from the Supreme Court on June 1, 1999.\n\n==Post-Court==\nHe served as the 11th Chancellor of [[York University]] from 2004 to 2008. He was an Honorary Colonel of the [[426 Transport Training Squadron]].\n\nIn 2002, Cory was made a Companion of the [[Order of Canada]].\n\nFollowing his retirement, Cory was appointed to conduct an independent inquiry into six particular deaths during \"[[the Troubles]]\" in Northern Ireland. The [[Cory Collusion Inquiry]] was established to investigate allegations of collusion between security forces and paramilitaries in those cases.\n\n==Personal life==\nCory was married to Edith Nash and had three children. He was a Mississaugan as of 2002.<ref>https://www.gg.ca/honour.aspx?id=8583&t=12&ln=Cory</ref>\n\nCory was chairman of the Ontario Civil Liberties Section of the [[Canadian Bar Association]] (\"CBA\"), president of the County of York Law Association, national director of the CBA and president of the Advocates' Society. He died on April 7, 2020.<ref>[https://www.skinnerandmiddlebrook.com/memorials/peter-cory/4181370/service-details.php Peter Cory 1925\u20132020]</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n<references />\n*{{CanadaSupremeCourtbio|cory}}\n*{{Canadian honour|Type=orc|ID=8583|accessdate=26 May 2010}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of [[York University]]|before=[[Avie Bennett]]|years=2004\u20132008|after=[[Roy McMurtry]]}}\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{clear|left}}\n{{Dickson-court}}\n{{Lamer-court}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cory, Peter}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of York University]]\n[[Category:Communications Security Establishment people]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:Justices of the Supreme Court of Canada]]\n[[Category:Justices of the Court of Appeal for Ontario]]\n[[Category:Lawyers in Ontario]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Osgoode Hall Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Windsor, Ontario]]\n[[Category:University of Western Ontario alumni]]\n[[Category:Canadian Queen's Counsel]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian judge}}\n{{Infobox Judge\n| image =   |\n| name          = Peter deCarteret Cory\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| office        = [[Puisne Justice]] of the [[Supreme Court of Canada]]\n| termstart     = February 1, 1989\n| termend       = June 1, 1999\n| nominator     = [[Brian Mulroney]]\n| appointer     = \n| predecessor   = [[Gerald Le Dain]]\n| successor     = [[Louise Arbour]]\n| office2       = \n| termstart2    = \n| termend2      = \n| nominator2    = \n| appointer2    = \n| predecessor2  = \n| successor2    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1925|10|25|mf=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Windsor, Ontario]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|2020|4|7|1925|10|25}}\n| death_place   = Mississauga\n| residence     = [[Mississauga, Ontario]]\n| spouse        = Edith Nash (deceased);  Mary Dayton \n}}\n'''Peter deCarteret Cory''', {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|CC|QC}} (October 25, 1925 \u2013 April 7, 2020) was a [[puisne judge]] of the [[Supreme Court of Canada]], from 1989 to 1999.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in [[Windsor, Ontario]], the son of Andrew and Mildred (Beresford Howe) Cory, he was educated at the [[University of Western Ontario]] (Assumption) receiving his [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in 1947 and at [[Osgoode Hall Law School]] receiving his law degree in 1950. He was called to the [[Ontario Bar]] in 1950.\n\n==Career==\nAs a pilot in the [[Royal Canadian Air Force]], he served overseas with 6th Bomber Group during [[World War II]], flying many combat missions. He was appointed to the [[Queen's Counsel]] in 1963. He practised law with Holden, Murdoch and was elected a Bencher of the [[Law Society of Upper Canada]] in 1971.\n\nCory was appointed to the [[Supreme Court of Ontario]] in 1974, the [[Court of Appeal for Ontario]] in 1981 and the Supreme Court of Canada on February 1, 1989. He retired from the Supreme Court on June 1, 1999.\n\n==Post-Court==\nHe served as the 11th Chancellor of [[York University]] from 2004 to 2008. He was an Honorary Colonel of the [[426 Transport Training Squadron]].\n\nIn 2002, Cory was made a Companion of the [[Order of Canada]].\n\nFollowing his retirement, Cory was appointed to conduct an independent inquiry into six particular deaths during \"[[the Troubles]]\" in Northern Ireland. The [[Cory Collusion Inquiry]] was established to investigate allegations of collusion between security forces and paramilitaries in those cases.\n\n==Personal life==\nCory was married to Edith Nash and had three children. He was a Mississaugan as of 2002.<ref>https://www.gg.ca/honour.aspx?id=8583&t=12&ln=Cory</ref>\n\nCory was chairman of the Ontario Civil Liberties Section of the [[Canadian Bar Association]] (\"CBA\"), president of the County of York Law Association, national director of the CBA and president of the Advocates' Society. He died on April 7, 2020.<ref>[https://www.skinnerandmiddlebrook.com/memorials/peter-cory/4181370/service-details.php Peter Cory 1925\u20132020]</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n<references />\n*{{CanadaSupremeCourtbio|cory}}\n*{{Canadian honour|Type=orc|ID=8583|accessdate=26 May 2010}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of [[York University]]|before=[[Avie Bennett]]|years=2004\u20132008|after=[[Roy McMurtry]]}}\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{clear|left}}\n{{Dickson-court}}\n{{Lamer-court}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cory, Peter}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of York University]]\n[[Category:Communications Security Establishment people]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:Justices of the Supreme Court of Canada]]\n[[Category:Justices of the Court of Appeal for Ontario]]\n[[Category:Lawyers in Ontario]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Osgoode Hall Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Windsor, Ontario]]\n[[Category:University of Western Ontario alumni]]\n[[Category:Canadian Queen's Counsel]]\n", "name_user": "All Hallow's Wraith", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Cory"}
{"title_page": "Saskatchewan Open", "text_new": "{{Infobox golf tournament\n| name             = Saskatchewan Open\n| image            = \n| location         = [[Saskatchewan]], [[Canada]]\n| establishment    = 1919\n| course           = \n| par              = \n| yardage          = \n| tour             = [[Canadian Tour]]\n| format           = [[Stroke play]]\n| purse            = \n| month_played     = \n| final_year       = 2016\n| aggregate        = \n| to-par           = \n| current_champion = \n| final_champion   = {{flagicon|DEU}} [[Max Rottluff]]\n}}\nThe '''Saskatchewan Open''' was a [[golf]] tournament on [[PGA Tour Canada]]. Founded in 1919, it was held annually except for minor interruptions until 1984. Having not been played from 1985 to 2007, it was revived in 2008. From 2010 the tournament had several changes of title, all reflecting it's host venue and sponsor, the [[Dakota Dunes Casino]]. It was last held in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dunes Open past participants on path to future golf success |newspaper=Star-Phoenix |location=Saskatoon, Saskatchewan, Canada |date=August 1, 2019 |page=B2 |first=Darren |last=Zary |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47218770/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Winners==\n{|class=wikitable\n!Year!!Venue<ref name=sask20s>{{cite web |url=http://golfsaskatchewan.org/article/the-twenties |title=The Twenties |website=Golf Saskatchewan |date=May 23, 2019 |first=Lori |last=Harvie |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=sask30s>{{cite web |url=http://golfsaskatchewan.org/article/the-thirties |title=The Thirties |website=Golf Saskatchewan |date=May 30, 2019 |first=Lori |last=Harvie |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=sask40s>{{cite web |url=http://golfsaskatchewan.org/article/the-forties |title=The Forties |website=Golf Saskatchewan |date=June 6, 2019 |first=Lori |last=Harvie |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>!!Winner<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://s3.amazonaws.com/golfcanada/app/uploads/golfsaskatchewan/2019/11/27130709/Open-2019.pdf |title=Saskatchewan Open / Dakota Dunes Open |work=Saskatchewan Golf |date=2019 |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>!!Score!!Ref\n|-\n!colspan=5|SIGA Dakota Dunes Open\n|-\n| 2016 || [[Dakota Dunes Golf Links|Dakota Dunes GL]] || {{flagicon|DEU}} [[Max Rottluff]] || 265 || \n|-\n| 2015 || Dakota Dunes GL || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Michael Letzig]] || 272{{efn|Letzig won following a playoff.}} || \n|-\n| 2014 || Dakota Dunes GL || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Matt Harmon]] || 264 || \n|-\n!colspan=5|Dakota Dunes Open\n|-\n| 2013 || Dakota Dunes GL || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Wil Collins]] || 267 || \n|-\n!colspan=5|Dakota Dunes Casino Open\n|-\n| 2012 || Dakota Dunes GL || {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Matt Hill (golfer)|Matt Hill]] || 269{{efn|Hill won following a playoff.}} || \n|-\n| 2011 || Dakota Dunes GL || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Joe Panzeri]] || 273 || \n|-\n| 2010 || Dakota Dunes GL || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Will Wilcox]] || 263 || \n|-\n!colspan=5|Saskatchewan Open\n|-\n| 2009 || Dakota Dunes GL || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Andres Gonzales]] || 274 || \n|-\n| 2008 || Dakota Dunes GL || {{flagicon|NZL}} [[Josh Geary]] || 270 || \n|-\n| 1985\u20132007 || colspan=3|''No tournament'' || \n|-\n| 1984 || Saskatoon G&CC || {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Brian French (golfer)|Brian French]] ||  || \n|-\n| 1983 || Saskatoon G&CC || {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Darrell McDonald (golfer)|Darrell McDonald]] || 213 || \n|-\n| 1982 || colspan=3|''No tournament'' || \n|-\n| 1981 || Wascana CC || {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Cec Ferguson]] || 204 || \n|-\n| 1980 || Saskatoon G&CC || {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Jerry Anderson (golfer)|Jerry Anderson]] || 214{{efn|Anderson won following a playoff.}} || \n|-\n| 1979 || Wascana CC || {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Jerry Anderson (golfer)|Jerry Anderson]] || 208 || \n|-\n| 1978 || Riverside CC || {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Roger Klatt]] || 211 || \n|-\n| 1977 || Wascana CC || {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Dan Halldorson]] || 207{{efn|Halldorson won following a playoff.}} || \n|-\n| 1976 || Holiday Park C